<HEADLINE> Fewer protesters expected in Philly than Seattle  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER BROWN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - The Republican National Convention is not
likely to draw as many people as the Seattle demonstrations did
last fall, protest organizers and police say with less than a month
before the convention.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10,000 people are expected in Philadelphia - far less
than the 40,000 who flooded Seattle, according to interviews with
veteran organizers and local group leaders. Up to 100,000 had been
forecast for the July 31-Aug. 3 event, but organizers quietly are
saying they expect much fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Several local organizers and police officials have said the buzz
on Internet discussion groups and among East Coast activist groups
is smaller for Philadelphia than it has been before recent large
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to tell, but I don't get the sense that this is
going to be as big as the other ones,'' Deputy Police Commissioner
Robert Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers in Los Angeles say up to 30,000 people could attend
demonstrations during the Democratic National Convention. But, the
West Coast event is likely to draw upon the same group of
demonstrators that protested the World Trade Organization meetings
last fall in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, the GOP convention will attract mostly East Coast
activists, including some of the 10,000 people who protested the
International Monetary Fund talks in Washington, D.C., in April.
More than 1,300 people were arrested, but police generally describe
the event as a success because there were few reports of property
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a pretty decentralized movement. There are so many
groups, we don't know who will come,'' said Beka Economopoulos of
the Rainforest Action Network, which was a primary organizer in
Seattle and has a smaller role in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the buzz was being created in Seattle. We knew it was
going to be big. There was buzz in Washington. And there's buzz for
the conventions.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest event, Unity 2000 on July 30, is expected to attract
up to 10,000, organizers estimate. The smaller Poor People's March
on July 31, which does not have a permit, is likely to draw fewer
than 3,000, Kensington Welfare Rights Union leader Cheri Honkala
said. And organizers of the July 29 march for universal health care
are predicting several thousand people.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance could skyrocket with the recent endorsement of Unity
2000 by the Pennsylvania AFL-CIO, which could bring thousands of
union workers to the protests. The Seattle movement gathered so
many people, in part, because of the unique partnership between the
unions and environmental advocates.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest challenges facing both conventions is that
colleges are not in session.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you look at Seattle and Washington, a lot of the people who
were there were students who organized on their campuses. They
organized together, then took buses together,'' said Deidre Sinnott
of the New York-based International Action Center, an anti-death
penalty group that plans to send about 100 members to protest the
GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, the most populous protests in
Philadelphia have been rallies for death row inmate Mumia
Abu-Jamal. More than 8,000 people attended a ''Millions for Mumia''
march to commemorate Abu-Jamal's 45th birthday in April 1999. And
more than 6,000 people attended a $15-per-head rally at Madison
Square Garden in New York this past May.
</P>
<P>
   But the Philadelphia-based Abu-Jamal support group plans only to
''have a contingent'' in the larger rallies. A day of direct action
- nontraditional street theater, human blockades and spontaneous
hotel rallies - is planned Aug. 1 to oppose the ''prison industrial
complex'' and support Abu-Jamal.
</P>
<P>
   But a key indicator could be this weekend's poor showing at a
rally during the National Governor's Meeting in State College.
Fewer than 200 people turned out for rallies in the central
Pennsylvania college town, despite the participation of key leaders
of events planned during the GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   Unity 2000 leader Michael Morrill, who spoke in State College
Sunday, has publicly predicted up to 50,000 people during the GOP
convention. But he agrees the numbers will be lower in Philadelphia
than Los Angeles or Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ''It could be thousands, it could be more. You never know until
it gets closer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On The Net:
</P>
<P>
   Unity 2000: http://www.unity2000.com
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Direct Action Group: http://www.thepartysover.org/
</P>
<P>
   International Concerned Family &AMP; Friends of Mumia Abu-Jamal:
http://www.mumia.org
</P>
</TEXT>
