<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Professors, Student in Thesis Clash  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE LOCKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) -- Chris Brown's faculty advisers had no
problem with the science in his master's thesis on abalone shells.
</P>
<P>
   But after reading his two-page ''disacknowledgements'' section
peppered with profanity and insults of faculty members, they
refused to put it in the school's library.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has Brown, 28, and the University of California at
Santa Barbara at an impasse: Is the critique protected speech, or
merely an untenable degree of disrespect?
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who believes it's his First Amendment right to preface
his paper the way he wants, has sued the university seeking to
force the school to put the thesis -- offending section included --
in the campus library.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of all places, the University of California, the place where
the Free Speech Movement started 30 years ago should not be
engaging in this kind of suppression of speech,'' said Paul
Hoffman, who is representing Brown in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   University administrators -- who didn't grant Brown his degree
for almost a year -- said he has the right to his opinions but that
they have a right not to endorse them.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the university is saying is, 'It is your
disacknowledgement, you go ahead and publish it,''' said Charles
Li, dean of the university's Santa Barbara's graduate division.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1999, Brown turned in his paper on the growth of abalone
shells to be filed in the campus library alongside the stacks and
stacks of other graduate student outpourings.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers had already approved the scientific content of his
paper titled ''The Morphology of Calcium Carbonate: Factors
Affecting Crystal Growth.''
</P>
<P>
   That changed after a librarian noted that instead of the usual
acknowledgments section thanking faculty, Brown had written a
''disacknowledgements'' section critical of faculty members.
</P>
<P>
   Among the comments: ''To the Dean and staff of the Graduate
Division, You fascists are the largest argument against higher
education there has ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   The faculty refused to grant a degree with the section included
and the battle began. Brown later removed the four-letter words,
but the professors still weren't happy.
</P>
<P>
   In May, after a number of appeals, the university granted Brown
his master's degree in science. Brown notes the decision came after
the school was contacted by a network news reporter; Li says the
timing was coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   However, the university still wouldn't allow the paper in the
library with insults attached. That prompted Brown's suit, filed
this month in federal court in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Li conceded it would have been simpler to let Brown's original
version languish quietly on library shelves. But he said the
faculty does not ''wish to put their stamp of approval'' on Brown's
vitriol.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, now working as a computer analyst for an Internet
company, said his case is about more than a frustrated graduate
student's lament.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's two issues -- writing what I wrote and there's the
issue of my ability to write what I wrote,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   University of California at Santa Barbara: http://www.ucsb.edu
</P>
<P>
   Foundation for Individual Rights in Education:
http://www.thefire.org
</P>
</TEXT>
