<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees Left Fielder Out for Season  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Shane Spencer of the New York Yankees will be
lost for the season after injuring his right knee fielding a ball
in left field in the first inning Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The outfielder tore the anterior cruciate ligament during the
Yankees' 2-0 loss to the crosstown-rival Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ''Shane's pretty distraught,'' general manager Brian Cashman
said. ''A lot of times you see this injury on a football field. He
needs a knee reconstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer stumbled while fielding Melvin Mora's first-inning
double, and immediately left the game, replaced by Felix Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The injury was originally called a twisted knee, but an
examination at Beth Israel hospital revealed the more serious
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman said surgery would be delayed for at least a week until
swelling goes down.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer was hitting .282 with nine homers and 40 RBIs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
