<HEADLINE> Mexico Drug Suspect's Lawyer Slain  </HEADLINE>
By GLORIA PEREZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOLUCA, Mexico (AP) -- A second attorney for a man accused of
being a major drug trafficker was found shot to death five weeks
after the suspect was ordered to stand trial on weapons charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexico State attorney general's office confirmed that the
bullet-riddled body of Eugenio Zafra Garcia was found Sunday in
front of his house in Toluca, the state capital west of Mexico
City.
</P>
<P>
   Another attorney, Gustavo Galvez Reyes, was found tortured and
suffocated to death in Mexico City after failing to win Jesus
Labra's release from house arrest following his arrest in Tijuana
on March 11.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers caught Labra while he was watching a youth football
game in which his son was a player. U.S. and Mexican officials
claim Labra is the financial mastermind of Mexico's most violent
drug organization, the Tijuana-based Arellano Felix brothers.
</P>
<P>
   On June 5, a judge ordered both Labra and Ismael Higuera
Guerrero, alleged to be one of the gang's top operators, to stand
trial: Labra on weapons charges and Higuera on allegations of
aiding and financing drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Both are being held at Mexico's maximum security prison at
Almoloya de Juarez, north of Toluca.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, Zafra had accused Mexico City police of
raiding and searching his office in Mexico City, but was unable to
produce proof that the police had committed the search.
</P>
<P>
   Zafra also had been the attorney for two men who had been
accused of participating in the March 1994 murder of presidential
candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio. In June 1995, he won the release of
Vicente Mayoral and his son, Rodolfo.
</P>
<P>
   A judge ruled that analysis of videotapes and other evidence
failed to support prosecution assertions that the Mayorals helped
clear the way for the assassin.
</P>
</TEXT>
