<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman leaving church suffers fractured skull in cement attack  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A 25-year-old woman walking from a Manhattan
church suffered a fractured skull when a would-be robber struck her
with a 5-pound chunk of concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Goldberg, 25, was in front of 105 E. 29th St. just after
noon Sunday when the man hit her with the concrete, tried
unsuccessfully to snatch her purse and then ran away, police said.
</P>
<P>
   She was in critical but stable condition Monday at Bellevue
Hospital. She was alert and oriented, and there was no apparent
sign of neurological damage, hospital officials said.
</P>
<P>
   An off-duty firefighter who had been driving by the scene of the
assault aided Goldberg, cradling her bleeding head and holding her
hand, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was just floored,'' area resident Deborah Brown told The
New York Times. ''But she was conscious, because she was squeezing
the hand of this guy who was helping her.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, a waitress who moved to New York four years ago, was
struck on the back of the head. In addition to the fractured skull,
she suffered two chipped teeth, cuts and bruises when she fell to
the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   She remained conscious throughout the day and was able to answer
questions from detectives, but she had no recollection of the
attack, police said. She spoke by telephone to her father in
Madison, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   At least two people witnessed the attack and described the
assailant, a man apparently in his 30s, as disheveled and possibly
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Area residents said building security cameras captured the
attack, but police would not comment on that. The chunk of cement,
believed to be a piece of sidewalk, was found nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg recently moved into Manhattan from Brooklyn and planned
to attend Columbia University later this year. She had just left
the Marble Collegiate Presbyterian Church, on 29th Street and Park
Avenue, and was heading for a nearby uptown subway station when the
attack occurred.
</P>
<P>
   It was at least the third such attack in New York during the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   In May, a 30-year-old Queens woman was hit by a brick and
robbed.
</P>
<P>
   And last November, Nicole Barrett, 27, was hit on the head with
a paving brick in midtown Manhattan while walking to work. She
underwent two brain operations and has returned to her home in
Texas for rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Paris Drake, an ex-convict and drug abuser, was charged with
second-degree attempted murder, first-degree assault and criminal
possession of a weapon in connection with Barrett's attack. He has
pleaded not guilty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
