<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Votes for Assad in Referendum  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA ABU-NASR
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- A month after President Hafez Assad's
death, his son took the final step toward succeeding him Monday,
standing as the only candidate in a nationwide presidential
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the vote is not in doubt. The only uncertainty is
how much of a percentage of ''yes'' votes Bashar Assad will
receive. In four of five referendums, all of them like this one
orchestrated by the ruling Baath party, his father won between 99.6
and 99.99 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament meets Tuesday for an extraordinary session in which
it will announce the referendum result and approve it.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's 9.44 million eligible voters -- more than half the
population -- began casting their ballots when the polls opened at 7
a.m. Syria's voters have a choice of checking either a green ring
that says ''yes'' or a gray one signifying ''no.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than use the offered pens, some voters pricked their
thumbs with sewing needles provided by voting officials and smeared
blood to mark their ballots.
</P>
<P>
   ''With our blood and our souls we sacrifice ourselves to you,''
crowds supporting Bashar Assad chanted as they went to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The main theme of the campaign leading up to the referendum had
been that Bashar Assad was the only Syrian capable of continuing
his father's policies. In his 30 years in power, the autocratic
Hafez Assad gave Syria stability after years of political upheaval,
coups and unrest.
</P>
<P>
   That Syria needed another Assad was drummed into voters by the
nation's powerful propaganda machine.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's the hope that promises prosperity for Syria and a
continuation of the late president's path which brought greatness
to this country,'' said Maher Qotranji, 42, a security guard.
</P>
<P>
   ''We shall continue the march with our leader Bashar,'' said a
banner near one of the polling stations.
</P>
<P>
   The government-controlled Syria Times said in an editorial
Monday that Syrians ''stress their allegiance to the principles and
values of the late great leader ... through casting their 'Yes'
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The huge loss of the great leader has not killed the hopes for
the revival of his sublime values,'' the paper added.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum is the last in a series of steps that the
political apparatus Hafez Assad left behind has taken to ensure the
succession of his son, a former eye doctor with little political
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of his father's death June 10, parliament amended
the constitution to lower the minimum age for a president from 40
to 34, Bashar Assad's age. In the days that followed, Bashar Assad
was promoted from colonel to general and declared commander of the
armed forces. The Baath party, which has enjoyed a monopoly in
Syria since 1963, made him its leader and nominated him as its
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Syrians have been holding victory parties since the People's
Assembly, Syria's 250-member parliament, approved the party's
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people turned out for huge rallies supporting
Bashar Assad, jamming the capital's streets, tooting horns and
waving portraits of the young leader.
</P>
<P>
   Giant portraits of both father and son are displayed on
government buildings and banners pledging allegiance to the younger
Assad are draped around squares.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitality tents have sprung in several Damascus neighborhoods,
where both bitter coffee and sweets are served to express sadness
over Hafez Assad's death and joy over his son's imminent
succession. Blazing torches held high by Arabian spears surround a
tent set up by Rami Makhlouf, Bashar Assad's cousin. A giant screen
projected a five-hour film on the Assad family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-10-00 0206 </TRAILER>
