<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harold Sack, buyer of $12 million Newport desk, was 89  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OCEANSIDE, N.Y. (AP) - Harold Sack, who paid $12.1 million for
an 18th century Newport desk-bookcase in 1989, died Saturday. He
was 89.
</P>
<P>
   Sack, America's foremost period furniture dealer, bought the
mahogany secretary at Christie's for what was then the highest
auction price ever for an item other than a painting.
</P>
<P>
   The desk, which he bought for a Texas financier, originally was
owned by Nicholas Brown, of Providence, R.I., and his family, for
whom Brown University is named.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1960s to the 1990s, Sack shattered auction price
records for American furniture. In 1977, he set the record of
$135,000 when he bought a Boston bombe chest. Three years later, he
pushed the record to $396,000, for a block-front Newport chest.
</P>
<P>
   He set the record again in 1983, paying $687,500 for a Newport
kneehole desk at Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   The $12.1 million Sack paid for the mahogany desk-bookcase in
1989 still is the record for American furniture. An 18th century
Italian cabinet sold at Christie's in London in 1990 for $15.2
million.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Sack, president of the Israel Sack gallery in
Manhattan, sold an 18th century Philadelphia Pembroke table for
more than $1 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-10-00 0239 </TRAILER>
