<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sail cruise commemorates 175th anniversary of the Erie Canal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NISKAYUNA, N.Y. (AP) - About 40 pleasure boats sailed down the
Erie Canal Sunday to commemorate the 175th anniversary of the
waterway by boating from one end of the canal to the other.
</P>
<P>
   The Canal Cruise and Trail Trek is a 17-day journey consisting
of a caravan of boaters and bikers who stop at 36 canal-side towns,
cities and villages.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cruise is held to promote awareness of the canal as a
recreational entity and promote awareness of the trail along the
canal,'' said John R. Jermano, former canal director and a
participant in the cruise.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise began Friday in Whitehall in Washington County and
will end on July 23 at the Inner Harbor in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The Erie Canal, which connected the Hudson and Lake Erie in
1825, was once an important commercial trade route that connected
the ports of New York and Albany to the western frontier.
</P>
<P>
   But the last remnants of commercial shipping left its banks in
1994 and it is now used exclusively for recreational purposes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
