<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Dip in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell slightly in early trading today as
investors digested Friday's big gains and looked forward to
earnings reports that are starting to trickle in this week.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, The Dow Jones
industrial average was down 3.89 at 10,632.09, while the Nasdaq
composite index was off 23.42 at 3,999.78
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 1.06 at 1,477.84.
</P>
<P>
   After the Dow gained 154 points on Friday and the Nasdaq picked
up 62 in reaction to a positive employment report, the market was
expected to at least mark time early in today's trading. But
analysts also anticipated that stocks would turn higher amid a
generally optimistic outlook for second-quarter earnings reports.
</P>
<P>
   A pleasant surprise came this morning from aluminum producer
Alcoa, whose earnings came in higher than expected. Alcoa rose
$2.25 to $29.875.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo!, expected to release its earnings report on Tuesday, fell
$4.50 to $111.25.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential Securities upgraded its rating on several retailers,
including Best Buy, up $1.81 to $72.56 and Circuit City Stores, up
$1.19 to $36.19.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers upgraded chip maker Applied MicroDevices, which
rose $5.31 to $87.31.
</P>
<P>
   In overseas trading, the Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1
percent. In afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.24
percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.04 percent, and France's
CAC-40 was down 0.05 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 102.18 million
shares, down from Monday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 0.43 to 528.65.
</P>
