<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Armstrong Takes Yellow Jersey  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREAS EVAGORA
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOURDES-HAUTACAM, France (AP) -- Lance Armstrong surged into the
overall lead in the Tour de France on Monday with a stunning climb
in the Pyrenees that placed him second in the 10th stage.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who came back from cancer to win last year's Tour,
overtook 1998 winner Marco Pantani and contender Richard Virenque
on the final climb in cold, driving rain.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was in his element.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today was about good tactics,'' he said. ''It was a good day
for me. I like these conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old Texan started the day in 16th place, 5:54
behind, but his stirring performance gave him the yellow jersey for
the first time this year.
</P>
<P>
   The only rider he couldn't catch was Spain's Javier Ochoa, who
won the first tough climb that was roughly the halfway point of the
21-stage race.
</P>
<P>
   Ochoa, who rides for the Kelme team, won the 127-mile stage from
Dax to Lourdes-Hautacam in 6 hours, 9 minutes, 32 seconds.
Armstrong finished 42 seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ochoa rode hard and led for so long,'' Armstrong said.
''Probably 99 percent of the people there were Spaniards cheering
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, who rides for the U.S. Postal Service Team, has said
all along that he can dominate other top riders in the mountains.
The Tour is won and lost in those grueling stages, with good
climbers able to make up dozens of minutes in the overall
standings.
</P>
<P>
   The vital moment of the day -- and perhaps the whole Tour -- came
eight miles from the end.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was well behind Ochoa, in a group with Pantani, Alex
Zulle and 1997 Tour champion Jan Ullrich.
</P>
<P>
   Pantani attacked. Armstrong stayed with the shaven-headed
Italian, but Zulle and Ullrich struggled to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong suddenly accelerated, storming past Pantani and
attacking the group ahead of him, which included France's Virenque,
last year's King of the Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ''Armstrong came through like a plane at the end,'' Virenque
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chilling winds, driving rain, mist and temperatures as low as 45
made it a day for brave riding. Several riders skidded down
treacherous mountain roads.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's brilliant ride Monday was similar to his showing a
year ago, when he won the first tough mountain leg -- the race's
ninth stage -- to increase the overall lead he had taken the stage
before.
</P>
<P>
   He never relinquished the yellow jersey thereafter, and is in
position to do the same this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Tour de France is very tough this year so I am not
counting on anything,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-10-00 1220 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000710.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA: 2006 World Cup Vote Is Final  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) -- Soccer's governing body Monday upheld
the contentious vote for the 2006 World Cup that was won by
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   One New Zealand member of FIFA's executive committee has said
threats from ''influential European interests'' gave him no
alternative but to abstain from the final balloting in which South
Africa lost by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''For legal reasons, the vote is over, it's final,'' FIFA
spokesman Andreas Herren said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The executive committee decided on the procedure itself, and
the procedure was then carried out in the presence of a Swiss
public notary and in complete compliance with the Swiss law,''
Herren said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on Zurich's Radio Z, FIFA general secretary Michel Zen
Ruffinen also stressed the election cannot be changed.
</P>
<P>
   Germany won 12-11 on Thursday in the vote by the 24-member
committee to upset South Africa, the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   If Charles Dempsey of New Zealand voted for South Africa to make
it 12-12, FIFA president Sepp Blatter would have cast the deciding
vote. Blatter had campaigned heavily for the African nation.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey described the threat as a simple one: ''It said if I
didn't vote for Germany I could be in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey, 78, announced his retirement as president of the
Oceania Football Confederation, on Sunday. He is a 36-year veteran
of international soccer administration.
</P>
<P>
   He said he didn't think his abstention would jeopardize South
Africa's bid. He added that other delegates had voted contrary to
expectations after a ''frenzy of bartering for votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey's conduct sparked outrage in South Africa and
condemnation by international soccer and political figures.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey refused to reveal the source of the threats. But his
daughter, Josephine King, the secretary-general of the Oceania
confederation, said her father had been pressured by UEFA.
</P>
<P>
   King said UEFA helped the fledgling Oceania confederation in the
past and was calling in favors, the New Zealand Press Association
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   FIFA and UEFA, European soccer's ruling organization, declined
to comment on Dempsey's accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey said he was exhausted from lack of sleep before the vote
because his telephone didn't stop ringing.
</P>
<P>
   A conversation with former South African president Nelson
Mandela didn't resolve his dilemma, Dempsey said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He appreciated and could understand,'' Dempsey said. ''And he
told me to do whatever I thought was right. Obviously, he wanted me
to vote for South Africa, there was no doubt about that.''
</P>
<P>
   A bribery scandal threatened to overshadow the ballot until a
German magazine claimed credit for placing hoax bribe letters under
the hotel doors of several delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey said he raised the attempted bribe with FIFA but was
unaware it was a hoax until the vote was taken.
</P>
<P>
   ''What really brought me down to earth was the bribe ... that's
when I took real fright,'' he said. ''That night was a nightmare in
my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-10-00 1224 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000710.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Climbs 24; Nasdaq Slips 13  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed Monday as investors mulled the
impact of a slowing economy: steadier interest rates but the
potential for weaker corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   At midday on Wall Street, The Dow Jones industrial average was
up 24.39 at 10,660.37, while the Nasdaq composite index was off
13.01 at 4,010.01.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 1.58 at 1,480.48.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were trading cautiously as they digested a positive
jobs report from the government on Friday. The report gave the
latest evidence that the U.S. economy is slowing in response to the
Federal Reserve's six interest rate increases since last June.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists now expect the Fed to leave rates unchanged for
the next few months. While that's good news for investors who were
unnerved earlier this year by the Fed's actions, there is still a
great deal of concern in the market that the cumulative effect of
the rate hikes will be a drop in corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Second quarter earnings annoucement begin in earnest this week.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody is kind of waiting and watching until corporate
earnings announcements hit full stride the end of this week,'' said
Alan Ackerman, senior vice president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The first Dow component to report profits, Alcoa, reported
higher-than-expected earnings. Shares of the aluminum producer rose
$2.25 to $29.875.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo!, expected to release its earnings report on Tuesday, fell
$4.625 to $111.875.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential Securities upgraded its rating on several beaten down
retailers, including Best Buy, up $3.063 to $73.813 and Circuit
City Stores, up $2.688 to $37.688.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers upgraded chip maker Applied MicroDevices, which
rose $4.313 to $86.313.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 345.45 million
shares, down from Monday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 1.23 to 529.45.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
