<HEADLINE> 'Harry Potter' Sales Break Records  </HEADLINE>
By RACHEL BECK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Harry Potter provided some cash register magic
for the nation's bookstores over the weekend, many of which tallied
record-breaking sales thanks to the much-hyped release of the
fourth book in the children's series.
</P>
<P>
   Booksellers -- big and small, on and off the Web -- reported
Monday that crowds packed their stores continuously since early
Saturday, when ''Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire'' went on sale
at 12:01 a.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
   Some chains even said that they were running low on books and
had already started talking with U.S. publisher Scholastic Inc. to
get more. Scholastic, meantime, already plans to print about 2
million more copies of the $25.95 book in the next few months,
adding to the 3.8 million copies generated during the first U.S.
print run.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc. had its biggest weekend in history, selling
502,000 of the new Harry Potter books as of the close of business
on Sunday night. That included about 100,000 through its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Keating, a spokeswoman for the New York-based chain,
added that the huge crowds helped boost overall sales, as the
people who flocked to the stores ended up buying other books as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, too, had a stellar weekend, with 389,000 total
orders coming in. Eighteen percent of the orders came from new
customers to its Web site, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   About 350,000 were pre-ordered before the book even went on sale
and about 40,000 orders were tallied since early Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   FedEx Corp. delivered 250,000 copies for Amazon on Saturday, 95
percent of the orders arriving at customers' homes by 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle-based Amazon said it still has plenty of copies of the
new book.
</P>
<P>
   The giant retailers weren't the only ones pulling in the big
crowds. The St. Paul, Minn.-based Red Balloon Bookshop had a steady
stream of shoppers visit over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Barb Bassett, a full-time bookseller at The Red Balloon, said
the store had about 500 pre-orders and then sold an additional 150
to 200 books. The bookstore still has around 100 books left.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rush has somewhat ended, but the books are still easing
out the door at a nice pace,'' Bassett said.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.bn.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.amazon.com
</P>
</TEXT>
