<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Failed Summit Could Hurt Barak  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA KING
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- When President Clinton invited Israel and the
Palestinians to come and talk peace at Camp David, he said there
was much to gain and little to lose by bringing the two sides
together now. That may no longer be true.
</P>
<P>
   Bloodied by political infighting, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak may find it impossible to tarry long in the United States
while right-wing opponents continue to campaign against him at
home.
</P>
<P>
   And the meltdown of Barak's governing coalition on the eve of
the summit might have left him so weakened that even if a landmark
accord were struck at Camp David, he could have trouble selling it
to the Israeli public.
</P>
<P>
   ''Never before has a national leader embarked on such a crucial
mission for his country amid such weakness,'' commentator Yoel
Marcus wrote in Monday's editions of Israel's Haaretz newspaper.
''And it certainly makes it difficult for Yasser Arafat, who will
not know whether whatever is agreed upon is ... signed only in
sand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians have made it clear they think it is the wrong
time for dealmaking. Arafat agreed under U.S. pressure to come to
the summit, but his top aides expressed pessimism over the chances
of success.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't trust the Israelis,'' Palestinian negotiator Yasser
Abed Rabbo said flatly as the Palestinians prepared to depart for
the United States. Upon arrival, Palestinian delegation sources
predicted the summit would lead to little more than an agreement to
hold another one later.
</P>
<P>
   Even with low expectations on the Palestinian side, failure
could intensify the kind of frustration that already fuels a daily
war of attrition in the Palestinian lands.
</P>
<P>
   After a Palestinian woman was killed and four others wounded
Sunday by Israeli army troops in the Gaza Strip near a Jewish
settlement, Palestinian Communications Minister Imad Falouji
protested furiously, brushing aside an Israeli apology that the
civilians had been caught in accidental cross-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our people's lives are not cheap,'' he said, warning that an
''explosion of violence'' could occur if no peace accord is
forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, writing in Newsweek magazine, acknowledged that the
ugly climate on the ground heightens the dangers should the summit
fail.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the parties do not seize this moment to make more progress,
there will be more hostility and more bitterness -- perhaps even
more violence,'' Clinton wrote in the magazine that appeared on
newsstands Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Barak can continue to govern despite the defection Sunday of
three rightist parties that accused him of being willing to concede
too much to the Palestinians. But without his parliamentary
majority, he can expect to be constantly harried by opponents as
they graphically demonstrated Monday when they delayed his
departure for the summit by staging no-confidence votes.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's political foes also put him on notice that
they will try to force early elections, which would put peacemaking
efforts on hold at a crucial time.
</P>
<P>
   ''Go to elections -- you have done enough damage!'' hawkish
former defense minister Ariel Sharon told Barak during Monday's
stormy parliamentary session. ''I call on ... everyone who wants a
better peace to join in calls for new elections.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak might very well win another election -- he won handily the
first time -- but an electoral campaign would mean Israel and the
Palestinians likely would miss a Sept. 13 deadline for signing an
accord. The Palestinians have said they will declare statehood that
day, treaty or no treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat already put off a statehood declaration once while Barak
was campaigning, in May 1999, and might have little appetite for
doing so again.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister insists that despite the worst political
turmoil of his year in office, ordinary Israelis still support his
peace efforts. The polls suggest he is right about that.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey published Monday in the Yediot Ahronot newspaper,
conducted among 502 Israelis with a margin of error of 4.5
percentage points, 53 percent said he had a mandate to make
concessions to the Palestinians, while 44 percent said he did not.
</P>
<P>
   But that support could slip while Barak is at Camp David. In his
absence, Jewish settlers -- infuriated by Barak's acknowledgment
that a peace accord could leave 50,000 of them outside the umbrella
of Israeli sovereignty -- intend to step up a campaign of mass
street protests.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to Barak's worries, political foes including conservative
former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu are increasingly claiming
the spotlight and finding a sympathetic audience.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am worried about the future and safety of the state of
Israel,'' Netanyahu said Monday as he toured northern Israel, where
many people are jittery over the pullout of Israeli troops from a
buffer zone in south Lebanon. ''I don't know details about promises
made to the Palestinians, but I am certainly worried over what I do
know.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Laura King, a correspondent in the Jerusalem
bureau, has covered Israeli-Palestinian peace efforts since 1997.
She will cover the Camp David summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-10-00 1516 </TRAILER>
