<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Firms Pledge Millions for AIDS  </HEADLINE>
By RAVI NESSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa (AP) -- With the international AIDS
conference under way, pharmaceutical companies have begun
announcing donations of medicine and money to help Africa fight the
disease that is ravaging the continent.
</P>
<P>
   But many government officials and activists are unimpressed:
They accuse the companies of trying to distract people from the
high price of their vital AIDS medicines.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want giveaways. ... We'd rather they reduce the price
of (all) their drugs,'' said Sharon Ekambaram of the HIV/AIDS
People's Treatment Action Campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest round in a long-running battle over AIDS
drugs, which are crucial for sufferers to live longer but so
expensive that many people -- and governments -- in Africa cannot
afford them. Drug companies say they're merely trying to recoup
money spent developing the drugs; activists say the companies are
set on reaping huge profits.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceutical giant Merck and Co. announced Monday it would
join the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation in donating $100 million
worth of medicine and money to help fight AIDS in Botswana, where
nearly 36 percent of adults are infected.
</P>
<P>
   The Gates foundation pledged $50 million over five years to help
the country strengthen its health care system. Merck promised to
match the value of the Gates' gift by managing the program and
donating antiretroviral medications that help control the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is going to make a world of difference for people living
with HIV in Botswana and that is something that cannot be
ignored,'' said Merck spokesman Jeffrey Turchio.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement followed a pledge by German drug company
Boehringer-Ingelheim. It promised Friday to offer the drug
nevirapine free for five years to developing countries to help
reduce mother-to-child transmission of HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Boehringer-Ingelheim and Merck are two of five major drug
companies that announced May 11 they would work with governments in
Africa and other poor regions to sharply cut the overall costs of
HIV/AIDS drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Though two months have passed since the announcement, the
specifics of that promise have yet to be worked out. Meanwhile, the
24.5 million Africans infected with the virus that causes AIDS
continue to suffer and die, activists say.
</P>
<P>
   High Court Justice Edwin Cameron, the most prominent member of
South Africa's government to openly talk of his HIV infection, on
Monday condemned the ''inequitous and immoral drug pricing and
international patent regime'' and issued ''a call to action for the
drug companies to immediately and without further delay, without
further dialogue, reduce prices dramatically and instantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Other activists dismissed the drug companies' offers as efforts
to generate good publicity during a conference where the companies
have been roundly condemned.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've all been trying to jump on the bandwagon of this
Durban 2000 conference,'' Ekambaram said. ''We know where their
interest lies -- not in our best interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Many donations are limited in amounts and time, she said,
asking: ''What happens after that?''
</P>
<P>
   Turchio, the Merck spokesman, said the companies are working to
solve the problem of high drug prices. He defended the offer made
in May.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not just a vague promise as I've heard it called. We have
made a firm commitment to do that,'' he said. ''We're not
undertaking this lightly. It's a serious commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the AIDS conference in Durban, speakers of varying
political stripes have almost uniformly united to demand cheaper
medicine. Nearly 5,000 people marched Sunday to demand greater
access to drugs for people in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, head of the African National
Congress' Women's League, told a rally before the march:
</P>
<P>
   ''The war against AIDS begins with the struggle against the drug
companies. It is incontestable that there are medicines that can
extend and dramatically improve the lives of people living with
HIV/AIDS. The struggle is now to get hold of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
