<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Upper House Rejects Putin's Plan  </HEADLINE>
By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The upper house of Russia's parliament on Monday
rejected President Vladimir Putin's bid to expand his powers and
reform the chamber, and warned of ''unpredictable consequences''
for the country if Putin succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   The upper house, or Federation Council, made the warning in a
six-point list of objections to Putin's moves that it submitted to
the lower house, the State Duma.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has proposed a package of bills aimed at trimming the
authority of regional governors who make up the Federation Council.
</P>
<P>
   The president describes his package as an attempt to force
regional bosses to comply with the country's 1993 constitution, but
critics say he is trying to eliminate checks and balances on
presidential power.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Duma approved one of the proposed laws, allowing
Putin to fire local officials and mayors, but the Federation
Council voted down another one, also previously approved by the
Duma, which would let the president dismiss governors who violate
laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Federation Council already has rejected the third measure,
which would have replaced governors in the upper chamber with
appointed senators. It later agreed to form a joint commission with
the Duma to work out a compromise on that bill.
</P>
<P>
   The two houses of parliament have been engaged in an intense
battle over Putin's plan, with the more powerful State Duma
strongly supporting it.
</P>
<P>
   In the list of objections submitted to the Duma, the upper house
insisted that there was no need to change the current structure of
the council, which complied with the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   It said Putin's plan, if implemented, would entail
''unpredictable negative consequences for the functioning of
institutions of state authority,'' Russian news reports said.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma's co-chairman of the conciliatory commission, Valery
Grebennikov, said the list included ''radical objections,''
suggesting compromise may be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   He accused the Federation Council of seeking to ''complicate the
work of the conciliatory commission, if not block it altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   Another commission member, Duma lawmaker Viktor Pokhmelkin, said
that because the upper house's disagreements were so large, he was
''afraid that in this situation the first meeting of the
conciliatory commission tomorrow will be its last.''
</P>
<P>
   If the compromise fails, the Duma can override the Federation
Council's veto with a two-thirds majority vote.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, provincial governors have assumed wide
authority in their regions. Putin, an advocate of strong-handed
federal policy, says tightening control over the regions is
essential to deal with economic problems and keeping Russia from
falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   While the two houses of parliament were locked in conflict, the
Kremlin was toying with the idea of creating a State Council made
up of selected regional leaders, Russian media reported, citing
well-informed Kremlin sources.
</P>
<P>
   Although the authority of this proposed body was unclear, it
appeared to be an attempt at splitting the Federation Council by
appeasing the most powerful governors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
