<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Troops Tense in Chechnya  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAIRTUP, Russia (AP) -- Russian soldiers suspiciously eyed
Chechen boys on the outskirts of this village Monday, fearing the
worst -- that the boys were spies for rebel fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian servicemen said the boys, who can be seen near any
village in the southern breakaway republic, count passing vehicles
and can alert Chechen militants once there is a large concentration
of federal troops in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Fear and tension are everywhere in Mairtup, 20 miles southeast
of the Chechen capital Grozny. The village school, which serves as
the federal army headquarters, is sealed off with barbed wire and
concrete plates, and parts of it are heavily mined to block rebel
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The stench of a makeshift toilet permeates the rooms, where
bullets and spent cartridges litter the floor. The soldiers here
say they can't wait until they are replaced in a week's time.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to be in constant tension. At any moment, fighting
might start here. And if the militants come, one third of the
village will take up arms,'' said a 20-year-old sergeant, Andrei
Tikhomirov.
</P>
<P>
   He glanced at Chechen men talking quietly in small groups,
passing women carrying buckets and bags, the elderly men sitting on
benches in front of their houses.
</P>
<P>
   Recent rebel attacks in Chechnya have heightened tension among
federal troops and sent Moscow scrambling to assert its control
over the area.
</P>
<P>
   Russian army columns, accompanied by helicopter gunships and
jets buzzing overhead, were on the move across Chechnya on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Aircraft pummeled suspected rebel positions in the Itum-Kale and
Vedeno regions of southern Chechnya, and heavy artillery bombarded
the thick forests of the southeastern Nozhai-Yurt district, near
the border with Dagestan, said a Chechen government official in the
northern town of Gudermes.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops clashed with rebels near the Dagestani border,
killing five militants, the military said. No Russian casualties
were reported, but both sides tend to underplay their losses.
</P>
<P>
   Federal forces also stepped up security on the ground,
reinforcing police stations and checkpoints in the wake of the July
2 series of truck bombings that killed at least 33 Russian
servicemen and wounded scores more.
</P>
<P>
   At checkpoints along Chechnya's roads, Russian troops
scrutinized pedestrians traveling from village to village. Most of
the civilians on the roads were women, as many Chechen men stay in
their villages, fearing run-ins with Russian troops suspecting them
of having rebel ties.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops nominally control most of Chechnya after having
rolled into the region in September, and are chasing rebel bands
hiding in the southern mountains. But they remain vulnerable to
sniping, bombings and hit-and-run attacks in lowland areas they
captured months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''The artillery is crushing them during the night. But what's
the use, they hate us and we hate them,'' said Sgt. Dmitry Kizilov,
a serviceman stationed in Mairtup.
</P>
<P>
   ''The psychology of these children must be changed,'' he said,
pointing at the boys. ''Their heroes are (warlord) Shamil Basayev
and (Chechen President Aslan) Maskhadov. And they hate us because
they were told we're the enemy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
