<HEADLINE> Israeli President Ewizman Resigns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman handed in his
resignation Monday, effectively ending a seven-year term that
turned sour when he was found to have acted improperly by accepting
gifts while in office.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the day marked ''the end of an era'' Weizman's top aide,
Aryeh Shumer, delivered the resignation letter to Avraham Burg,
speaker of Israel's parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the resignation takes effect 48 hours later. There
will be no Israeli president until July 31, when lawmakers will
vote by secret ballot between former Prime Minister Shimon Peres
and legislator Moshe Katsav of the opposition Likud party.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have accomplished a lot, and I am leaving feeling good and
satisfied,'' Weizman said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman's resignation came after the attorney general ruled that
Weizman had acted improperly. However, the 76-year-old president
had said previously that he would resign sometime this year, citing
ill health and the implications of a police investigation into more
than $300,000 in gifts he accepted from a French millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman became embroiled in controversy after a journalist
alleged he had received $453,000 from Edouard Sarousi, a French
textiles magnate.
</P>
<P>
   Police concluded that Weizman's failure to report the money
constituted fraud and breach of public trust, but that the statute
of limitations on those charges had run out.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman has admitted receiving $350,000 but insisted the money
was a private gift and never affected any of his decision-making
while president.
</P>
<P>
   Peres, a Nobel Peace Prize winner and architect of the Oslo
Accords which launched the Israeli-Palestinian peace process, is
considered the front-runner in the race. However, the current
political turmoil stemming from the collapse of Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's coalition on Sunday could affect the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Shas, the ultra-Orthodox party that dealt a serious blow to
Barak by pulling out on Sunday, is also seen to be playing a strong
role in determining the results of the presidential race, with its
17 votes.
</P>
<P>
   He received the 1994 Nobel Peace Prize for trying to end the
decades-long conflict. Although he is revered abroad as a
statesman, he has drawn criticism from the more hawkish elements at
home as being too conciliatory to Israel's Arab neighbors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
