<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prominent Russian Executive Killed  </HEADLINE>
By ALEXEI VLADYKIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   YEKATERINBURG, Russia (AP) -- Two gunmen killed the general
director of Uralmashzavod, one of Russia's biggest machine-tool
manufacturers, in a brazen daylight attack Monday in this Ural
Mountains city.
</P>
<P>
   The killing of Oleg Belonenko was one of the most high-profile
homicides in the Russian business community, and came as Moscow is
trying to show a strong hand in dealing with crime and corruption
while trying to woo investors into its aging industries.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone should feel the danger,'' Kakha Bendukidze, chief
executive officer of the Uralmash-Izhora Group, told reporters in
Moscow. Uralmashzavod is a subsidiary of his group.
</P>
<P>
   Belonenko was shot outside the company dormitory where he had
been living, as he was getting into his company car to go to work.
He died in surgery, said Tatyana Stepanova, a spokeswoman for
police in Yekaterinburg, about 900 miles east of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Belonenko's driver was wounded in the chest, and he, too, died
in the hospital, Stepanova said.
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting, eyewitnesses saw two men in track suits with
hoods running away, NTV television reported.
</P>
<P>
   Police could not immediately cite a motive for the killing, but
they were questioning Uralmashzavod employees about whether
Belonenko had received threats and any recent business discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what this killing could be connected with,'' said
Yevgeny Porunov, chairman of the regional parliament. ''Oleg
Belonenko was a manager, not a stockholder, so it's difficult to
speak about a (dispute over) redistribution of property.''
</P>
<P>
   Bendukidze said he believed the killing was a contract murder,
but professed surprise that Belonenko or Uralmashzavod were
targeted.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought this type of thing took place only where there was
an evident conflict'' or criminal activity, he said. He said there
was neither at Uralmashzavod.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, the huge plant has been a target of
organized crime groups intent on winning control over Russian
industry. One of the biggest mob groups in Russia even co-opted the
name.
</P>
<P>
   Belonenko's predecessor as general director, Viktor Korovin,
reportedly was unable to parry criminals' efforts to infiltrate the
plants. Under his watch, more than 100 commercial firms were
created on the plant's premises to sell spare parts, but the
profits did not return to the holding -- and some of them were
controlled by criminal groups, local officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Belonenko, 52, was named general director of Uralmashzavod in
December, after serving two years as deputy director. Before
joining the Urals giant, he served as a vice president of the huge
Kamaz truck plant.
</P>
<P>
   Belonenko launched a campaign to improve labor discipline at the
plant, including allowing workers to smoke only in designated
areas.
</P>
<P>
   He also took on the Uralmashzavod mob, filing lawsuits against
the commercial firms and demanding that they stop using the name or
pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   The plant flourished under Belonenko, winning profitable
contracts to provide metallurgical equipment to Russian
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   It was additionally buoyed by high world oil prices and the weak
ruble, which have helped revive Russian industry by making imports
less competitive. Bendukidze said that the company's order book had
swelled by 70 percent this year over last.
</P>
<P>
   According to company data, the plant's productivity rose 58
percent this year, and the average wage rose 89 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-10-00 1600 </TRAILER>
