<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Cross issues 'blood emergency' in Connecticut  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Blood supplies remained tight in Connecticut on
Monday, the
first full day after the American Red Cross said its inventories
had reached dangerously low levels, but hospitals reported no
immediate problems.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Connecticut on Sunday became one of 31 Red Cross regions across
the nation that have declared blood emergencies. Thirty-six regions
make up the national Red Cross system, accounting for about half of
the nation's blood supply.
</P>
<P>
   Managers at hospitals in Hartford, New Haven and elsewhere said
they were keeping a close eye on supplies, but said no surgeries
had been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ''Currently, we are being very cautious with the blood we use,''
said Dr. Edward Snyder, director of the blood bank at Yale-New
Haven Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital is particularly low on negative blood types, Snyder
said. In an emergency, Yale-New Haven would use positive blood
types. Still, he said, the Red Cross keeps an emergency supply
which would likely be tapped in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Herbert Silver of Hartford Hospital said while there is no
current problem, a major trauma could change that situation
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   One hospital that has maintained its full inventory - 50 units
each of types O and A and 15 units of other types - was William W.
Backus Hospital in Norwich. The region around the hospital is
bracing for tens of thousands of visitors this week attending a
''tall ships'' festival in New London.
</P>
<P>
   The last blood emergency in Connecticut was declared more than a
year ago, Red Cross spokeswoman Lynn Townshend said.
</P>
<P>
   The blood supply in Connecticut was depleted by a monthlong
strike of Red Cross blood collection workers that ended on June 3.
The Red Cross warned last month that a shortage of blood was
reaching a crisis point in Connecticut, forcing the agency to
restrict the amount of blood distributed to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Those wishing to donate blood can reach the Red Cross at 1
(800)-GIVE-LIFE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-10-00 1605 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
