<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HMO dropouts worry seniors, lawmakers  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILFORD, Conn. (AP) - Sebastian Boscarino, 78, suffers from
diabetes, has had two heart attacks and takes nine prescription
drugs a day.
</P>
<P>
   So he was not happy to hear that his Medicare health maintenance
organization, Anthem Blue Cross &AMP; Blue Shield, plans to quit the
Connecticut market.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm kind of boxed in,'' Boscarino said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week 20 private health insurance companies announced that,
beginning next year, they will pull out of more than 440 counties
around the country where they now provide ''Medicare Plus Choice''
plans to about 875,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, three HMOs that currently offer Medicare Plus
programs are withdrawing: Anthem Blue Cross &AMP; Blue Shield, Aetna
U.S. Healthcare and Cigna Inc.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth HMO, Physicians Health Services, is pulling out of
Litchfield and Middlesex counties.
</P>
<P>
   Boscarino said he considers himself lucky because the company he
retired from, Accurate Forging of Bristol, agreed to pay for his
health insurance as part of his retirement package.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to ask my company to find me another HMO or give me
the money to pay for supplemental health insurance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boscarino was one of about 200 senior citizens who packed the
Milford Senior Center on Monday to discuss the recent withdrawals
by several Medicare HMOs in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Rosa DeLauro, D-Conn., who organized meetings in
Milford and Hamden, urged seniors not to panic, noting that the
pullouts will not become effective until Jan. 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got some time here to make the right decisions for
yourselves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There are four other HMOs that will continue to offer Medicare
Plus programs in all or part of Connecticut. The number of choices
remaining varies from county to county.
</P>
<P>
   Many senior citizens enroll in Medicare Plus to get prescription
drug coverage and other benefits they can't get with the
traditional fee-for-service Medicare program. They pay an
additional premium and must stay within the HMO network of
providers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the seniors who attended the meeting in Milford said
they will shop around for another HMO or revert to traditional
Medicare, but then be forced to buy a supplemental policy.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Benoit, 69, also covered by Anthem Blue Cross &AMP; Blue
Shield, said he's concerned supplemental insurance will be too
costly for him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm having a tough time now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A survey conducted by the American Association of Health Plans
found that 14 of 18 companies leaving the program cited inadequate
federal reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Connecticut Democrats - U.S. Rep. Sam Gejdenson and
U.S. Sen. Christopher Dodd - held a similar meeting Monday in
Middletown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-10-00 1605 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000710.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Service Weathers Forecast Storm  </HEADLINE>
By LIB QUAID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- From the National Weather Service, the
forecast for the New York Mets' home opener: scattered showers over
Shea Stadium, with heavier rainfall expected to hold off until
after the game. ''THIS FORECAST WILL BE UPDATED LATER THIS MORNING.
GO METS!'' the statement read.
</P>
<P>
   The April 3 announcement seemed innocent enough but it angered
commercial forecasting companies, a $250 million to $300 million a
year business. They saw it as unwelcome competition -- an attempt by
the weather service to provide for free the information they sell.
</P>
<P>
   The weather service acknowledged the ''site specific'' forecast
violated its policy and says it took action. But now Congress has
gotten involved.
</P>
<P>
   The House passed a spending measure that includes language
making it illegal for the weather service to provide information
and services handled by commercial companies. Sen. Sam Brownback,
R-Kan., may add it to the Senate version of the bill, which is
stalled in the Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we were hearing from a number of people is that they're
getting a lot of direct competition from the weather service,''
said Brownback, who serves on the Commerce panel.
</P>
<P>
   The weather service, created in 1870, is the official voice for
severe weather watches and warnings. It also provides, for free,
weather and climate forecasts to government agencies, private
companies and the public.
</P>
<P>
   Private forecasting companies, which emerged in the 1960s and
'70s, package the free weather service data and sell it to
newspapers, television and radio stations, agriculture and
transportation companies, sports teams and other customers.
</P>
<P>
   Creating forecasts for special events or venues is not part of
the weather service's mission, said Ed Johnson, the agency's acting
director of strategic planning and policy.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are a major, major wholesaler of weather information that
drives the whole weather information business,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The weather service and other foes of the legislation say it
could force citizens and local governments to pay private companies
for information they now get for free.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Sierra, president of the National Weather Service
Employees Organization, said private companies have already started
to provide information that used to be disseminated by the weather
service.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the reason we were forced out of providing service to
the agricultural community,'' said Sierra, who works at the weather
service office in Brownsville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed competition clause says the weather service ''shall
not provide, or assist other entities to provide, a service if that
service is currently provided or can be provided by commercial
enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Commercial enterprise'' means businesses such as Wichita,
Kan.-based WeatherData Inc., which puts out a weather page used by
some newspapers as well as site-specific forecasts WeatherData does
for railroad and airline companies.
</P>
<P>
   Company President Mike Smith is lobbying for the legislation, as
are State College, Pa.-based AccuWeather and other commercial
forecasters. Smith argues the agency should stay out of the
specific business-to-business element of weather forecasting.
</P>
<P>
   ''Other government agencies don't do that,'' he said, ''and
neither should the weather service.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith was moved to action because he says the weather service
offered a high-resolution radar service to a Norman, Okla.,
company, but not his. Whenever possible, the agency is supposed to
share such technology with any company or agency that wants it.
</P>
<P>
   The weather service says not every site -- including its own
field offices -- is equipped to handle the service. In this case,
Johnson said, radar was provided to the University of Oklahoma and
not the company, although the university was involved in setting up
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Since debate began on Capitol Hill, the weather service has
offered the radar service to Smith's company.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service: http://www.nws.noaa.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Senate Commerce Committee:
http://www.senate.gov/(tilda)commerce/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-10-00 1607 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000710.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dead man pulled from Passaic River  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - State police pulled the body of an Essex
County man from the Passaic River in Newark on Monday morning,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The man's name was not immediately released pending notification
of his family, said Charlotte L. Smith, executive assistant Essex
County prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   The time and cause of death remained under investigation, Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   The body was that of a black male was wearing tan Levi's Docker
pants and a gray T-shirt but no shoes, said Sgt. Al Della Fave, a
spokesman for the state police.
</P>
<P>
   It was found floating underneath the Stickel Bridge, which
carries Interstate 280 over the Passaic River.
</P>
<P>
   Those with information are asked to call the Newark Bay marine
unit of state police at (973) 578-8173.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
