<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five indicted in Central Park attacks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - The judge hearing the case of the young men
accused of attacking women in Central Park last month said Monday
that he expects the defendants to go to trial in September.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Thompson, spokeswoman for the Manhattan district
attorney's office, said 26 men have been indicted on felony charges
in the June 11 incidents; one is charged with misdemeanors. The
number could change as the investigation continues.
</P>
<P>
   Most are charged with sex abuse and riot for allegedly dousing
women with water, chasing them, stripping some and fondling others.
Nearly 60 women complained they were molested.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Bernard Fried scheduled dates for
pretrial conference and motions after some lawyers said they wanted
time to review amateur videotapes that captured the activities of
some of their clients. The also wanted a chance to talk to
prosecutors about possible plea deals.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fried released defendant Isaiah Forbes, 18, who is
charged with sex abuse and riot, after Assistant District Attorney
Leemie Kahng told the judge that her office was consenting to his
release without bail pending further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Other defendants in this case have been released with the
consent of prosecutors when preliminary investigations have failed
to show definitely that the defendants were involved in the attacks
on the women.
</P>
<P>
   Fried set a trial date of Sept. 11 for all defendants who have
been indicted. He scheduled the arraignments for July 24 and July
31.
</P>
<P>
   Kahng told Fried that the felony defendants have been indicted
but those indictments had not been filed with the court. This meant
that the defendants could not be arraigned until later this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
