<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holocaust film director Laurel Vlock dies at 74  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WOODBRIDGE, Conn. (AP) - Laurel Vlock, a producer and director
whose films about Holocaust survivors served as models for Steven
Spielberg's Shoah Foundation, has died. She was 74.
</P>
<P>
   Vlock died Saturday from injuries sustained in a car accident
Friday. A private funeral service was held Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979 she founded the Holocaust Survivors Film Project Inc.,
which videotaped testimony from Holocaust survivors. The films are
deposited at the Fortunoff Video Archive for Holocaust Testimonies
at Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   Vlock won an Emmy Award in 1981 for ''Forever Yesterday,'' a
documentary about Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Her son, Michael Vlock, said his mother feared the lessons of
the Holocaust would be lost if survivors' stories were not
recorded.
</P>
<P>
   ''She had to dig - and dig deep - to find people and convince
them to open up and speak about experiences they didn't want to
open up about,'' Michael Vlock said.
</P>
<P>
   Vlock had hosted the television program ''Dialogue with Laurel
Vlock'' since 1966. Her other television credits include ''Meet the
President'' in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   She received her bachelor's degree from Cornell University and
her master's degree at Queens College. She was born in New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Vlock is survived by her 102-year-old mother, Rose Fox; her
husband, Jay Vlock; three children; and nine grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-10-00 1611 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000710.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman accused of bilking grandfather, others  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DOVER PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - A 27-year old woman was arrested for
duping 26 people, including her grandfather, into giving her over
$1 million, police said.
</P>
<P>
   In a scheme that began six years ago, Tina Marie Hannan
allegedly told her grandfather, who raised her, and people he knew
that she worked for a prominent Poughkeepsie insurance company.
Saying that the Internal Revenue Service was closing the company
for bookkeeping errors that were not legitimate, she convinced him
that she was suing the IRS in a multi-million dollar lawsuit,
according to state police Investigator John Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Hannan told contributers that she needed money lawyers, interest
penalties and fees. Ryan said she promised victims ''an inordinate
payoff'' for their efforts and money.
</P>
<P>
   Hannan was charged with two counts of second-degree grand
larceny. The investigation continues.
</P>
<P>
   Police said her grandfather unwittingly persuaded his friends to
contribute large sums of cash to Hannan. Police said he lost
hundreds of thousands of dollars and has since moved to a trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Working on a tip, police apprehended Hannan on Sunday as she
came to her grandfather's trailer to pick up $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   Dover Plains is 75 miles north of New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
