</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000710.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relatively few reap benefits of programs to lower power costs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JAMESTOWN, N.Y. (AP) - Sam Teresi's lights burn just as brightly
as Tony Caprino's. But Teresi's electric bill is a fraction of his
Village of Lakewood neighbor's.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Jamestown, where Teresi lives, is one of 46 small
cities, towns and villages in New York to qualify for Niagara Power
Project electricity, the cheapest in the nation, and run their own
electric systems. Federal law guarantees 40 percent of Niagara
power to the state's municipal utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Lakewood and the rest of the state have to contend with rates 62
percent higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Caprino, mayor of Lakewood for the past 20 years, pays Niagara
Mohawk 12 cents a kilowatt hour, while Teresi, in his first year as
mayor of his Chautauqua County city, pays four cents.
</P>
<P>
   Caprino would like Lakewood to start its own municipal utility,
but is finding out it is an expensive prospect. The state's Public
Service Commission ruled in 1998 that communities wanting to leave
a private utility had to pay an exit fee based on the utility's
past investments in the area. That is in addition to paying for the
electric lines a municipal utility would take over.
</P>
<P>
   In Buffalo, Niagara Mohawk estimates the exit fee alone at $900
million.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Alfred Coppola, who pushed for a city municipal power
system while a member of the Buffalo Common Council, calls that
figure inflated. His experts put the exit fee at $295 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''They blame everyone but themselves,'' he told The Buffalo
News, citing Niagara Mohawk's costly forays into troubled nuclear
power. ''The exit fee is basically to cover their poor management
over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Niagara Mohawk says it's only fair.
</P>
<P>
   ''What the regulatory contracts we operate under are attempting
to prevent is unfair cost shifting,'' spokesman Stephen Brady told
the newspaper. ''If Community X decides to leave our network, we
have incurred costs to serve these customers.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If the state allows communities to leave without paying those
costs,'' he said, ''those costs are going to be passed on to the
existing customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Lakewood is haggling with Niagara Mohawk over its final bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''They started out at $39 million,'' Caprino said. ''We're down
to $14.5 million, and we're still working on it. I think it's
looking pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   The village has hired Washington, D.C., attorney Cathy Fogel,
who helped Massena start the state's last municipal utility nine
years ago. That northern New York city has cut power rates from 13
cents to four cents a kilowatt hour.
</P>
<P>
   But Fogel said new municipal power systems should not expect
such immediate benefits because most of the power is allocated
through long-term Niagara contracts with existing municipal
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Jamestown, a busy furniture- and metal-manufacturing city in the
early part of the 20th Century, got into the electricity business
when it bought out a private electric company in the 1920s under
the leadership of Mayor Samuel Carlson.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was his Swedish stubbornness and his belief in municipal
ownership of every kind that did it,'' said historian Helen
Ebersole. Jamestown stopped buying private electricity and
generated its own power at the Samuel A. Carlson Plant but never
bought much hydroelectric power until the administration of former
Mayor Stan Lundine, who later became a congressman and lieutenant
governor under Gov. Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was kind of a silly pride in generating our own power,''
Lundine said. ''I remember asking, how much did it cost to generate
power? It was about 4.5 mils (cents per kilowatt). And about how
much to buy Niagara power? It was about 1 mil.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, 'Well, let's see how much we can buy.' I mean, you
have to take advantage of it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jamestown today gets Niagara's third-largest allocation - 72
megawatts - behind fellow municipal utilities Plattsburgh and
Fairport. The Carlson Plant is capable of producing an additional
53 megawatts of power but usually generates only one-third of what
the city needs. It is a selling point for Jamestown to keep
manufacturers, such as Monofrax, a power-intensive company that
makes glass bricks for kilns.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we were to lose this allocation, I'm concerned many of the
larger companies would say, 'If the rates are going up, we're going
to have to go where it's more economical,''' said Michael Darroch,
deputy general manager of Jamestown's Board of Public Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Besides delivering bargain-rate electricity, the city's public
utilities last year contributed $2.16 million to the city and
school treasuries in lieu of taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Niagara Mohawk and New York State Electric &AMP; Gas are out to
make a profit,'' Darroch said. ''Our object is to keep our utility
rates low. Our profit is returned to our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2.4 million-kilowatt Niagara Power Project is up for its
first relicensing in half a century in 2007. C.D. ''Rapp''
Rappleyea, as chairman and chief executive of the New York Power
Authority, will oversee negotiations for the project's new license
but refused to speculate on who will get what when negotiations are
over. He said the power authority won't start the process until
2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
