<HEADLINE> Federal Judges Tosses Out Fraternity Lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM KATES
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - A federal judge has ruled that Hamilton
College did not violate antitrust laws by requiring students to
live on campus and not in fraternity houses.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Norman Mordue found that ''there is no
genuine issue as to any material fact'' in the 1995 antitrust case
and ordered that it be dismissed in its entirety in a decision
rendered June 29.
</P>
<P>
   The fraternities sued the college under the Sherman Antitrust
Act, arguing that the residential life plan adopted by the school
in 1995 had made the college a ''monopolist'' in providing services
to students.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, all students were required to live in
campus-provided housing and purchase a five-meals-a-week dining
plan. College officials said the rule was necessary to integrate
academic and social life and to cut down on the use of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Mordue sided with Hamilton's lawyers, who had argued that
because the college is only one of many competing institutions, it
cannot monopolize any collegiate market by itself. The judge added
that the fraternity's antitrust claims were no longer at issue
because current students are made aware of Hamilton's residential
policies before enrolling.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think Judge Mordue was clearly right when he ruled that
Hamilton College competes with a number of other colleges to enroll
students and that a market definition that fails to take account of
that is legally insufficient,'' attorney Robert Bell, the school's
lawyer, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. District Judge Rosemary Pooler dismissed the lawsuit
in 1996 only to have the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reverse
her ruling. The appeals court concluded that the fraternities had
not been given a sufficient opportunity to plead their case and
sent it back to the district court.
</P>
<P>
   College president Eugene M. Tobin praised Mordue's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''We maintained that the market definition used by the
fraternities in this lawsuit was legally indefensible, and we're
pleased the court agreed with the college on that fundamental
point,'' Tobin said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the plan has achieved its intent, which was to
produce ''a stronger pool of applicants, especially among high
ability female students, a more intellectually focused student body
and an improved academic reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Allowing the fraternities' definition to stand might have been
precedent-setting in a number of other ways colleges conduct their
businesses,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   The fraternities' law firm was still reviewing the decision and
not able to comment, said attorney Cheryl Browning.
</P>
<P>
   The 188-year-old liberal arts college, located in Clinton, N.Y.,
has an enrollment of about 1,700 students. The fraternities which
filed the lawsuit were the Psi Chapter of Psi Upsilon Inc., the
Hamilton Chapter of Alpha Delta Phi Inc., Beta of Sigma Phi Society
Inc. and Delta Kappa Epsilon Society of Hamilton College.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
