<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Off-Islander's' Guide to Nantucket  </HEADLINE>
By JEROME MINERVA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTUCKET, Mass. (AP) -- Being on an island somewhere out in the
Atlantic has its advantages. There is the sense of getting away
from it all and rediscovering what makes life worth living.
</P>
<P>
   And that quite simply is the allure of Nantucket. But with that
allure comes a price.
</P>
<P>
   The following is an ''off-islander's'' unofficial guide to what
to look for on the island.
</P>
<P>
   BEST VALUE: The 2000 visitor pass for all nine offerings by
the Nantucket Historic Association for $10; the 90-minute sail
aboard Endeavor for $22.50; and the $1 shuttle bus around the
island.
</P>
<P>
   WORST VALUE: A $20 taxi ride from Siasconset to Miacomet.
</P>
<P>
   DINING: Jared Coffin House (29 Broad St., 800-248-2405) offers
a seafood buffet on Sunday and Wednesday for $26.95. The
smorgasbord offers every shellfish imaginable, plus two types of
fresh fish and to top it off, half a lobster. If you want to feel
like royalty, then 21 Federal (21 Federal St., 508-228-2121) is
the place. Entrees run from $25-$33, but its worth it just for the
ambiance and service. Chanticleer (9 New St., Siasconset,
508-257-6231) is unmistakably French and the only four-star
restaurant on the island. Breakfast at Topper's (120 Wauwinet
Road, Wauwinet, 508-228-0145) is said to be an out-of-body
experience.
</P>
<P>
   PUB FOOD: Atlantic Cafe (15 South Water St., 508-228-0570) is
the most popular and for good reason: The food is good and the
price is reasonable.
The Brotherhood (23 Broad St.) Try the Cheddar soup and wash it
down with a Whale's Tail ale.
</P>
<P>
   NIGHTLIFE: Mondays are fun at the Rose and Crown (23 South
Water St., 508 228-2595) It's karaoke night Sunday and Monday, and
DJ Ken Wade pulls no punches with some very over-the-top humor.
The Muse (44 Surfside Road, 508-228-MUSE) serves up the best live
entertainment on the island. And if singalongs are your thing, then
The Club Car (Lower Main St., 508-228-1101) is for you. The bar
is a former Nantucket Railroad car, the last remnant of a railroad
derailed in 1918 when its engine was sold to France.
</P>
<P>
   BIKING: There are at least a half dozen bike trails. If you're
only going to do one, try the 16-mile loop out Polpis Road toward
Wauwinet and Siasconset and back on Milestone Road to town. Along
the way you'll see The Life Saving Museum, Sesachacha Pond, Altar
Rock, The Moors, a cranberry bog, Sankaty Head Golf Club and
finally Siasconset village.
</P>
<P>
   GOLFING: Miacomet Golf Club (12 West Miacomet Road,
508-325-0333) is the best public course on the island. It's $29 for
nine holes.
Siasconset Golf Club (Milestone Road, 508-257-6596) is the easiest
to get onto and the cheapest ($25 for nine), but it's below par in
quality.
</P>
<P>
   TOURING: Nantucket Bike Shop (Steamboat Wharf, 508-228-1999)
has mo-peds and bicycles. Young's Bicycle Shop (Steamboat Wharf,
508-228-1151) has bicycles and rents jeeps. Nantucket Whalewatch
(Straight Wharf, 800-322-0013) Reservations are recommended for
this excursion, which runs from the end of July to Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   LODGING: Jared Coffin House (see listing above) is the most
popular. Rates are from $100 to $325. Honorable mention goes to the
Cliff Lodge (9 Cliff Road, 508-228-9480) with rates from $150 to
$300. The best value is
The Periwinkle Guest House (North Water St., 800-588-0074) with
rates from $55 to $475.
</P>
<P>
   TRANSPORTATION: The Steamship Authority (508-548-5011) and
Hy-Line Cruises (508-778-2600) run nearly continuous ferry service
to the island from Hyannis, Mass. Short on time? The Flying
Cloud@, a high-speed ferry, gets you there faster. Several major
and local airlines have regularly scheduled flights to Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   FISHING: You can surf cast from almost anywhere on the island,
but the points (Great, Eel and Smith's) are considered the best.
There are several sport fishing charters for hire. Most go for
about $65 for two and one-half hours. Bluefish and stripers are
running until the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   BIRDWATCHING: Author Ken Blackshaw recommends using the five
wharves in town to view the island's indigenous birds. Bring a pair
of binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   COMING EVENTS: The Actors Theatre of Nantucket will be
presenting an abridged version of the play ''The Complete Works of
William Shakespeare.'' Performances will run from the middle of
July to the middle of August in the lower level theatre of the
Methodist Church at 2 Centre St. All seats are $16. Call (228)-6325
for more information.
</P>
<P>
   On July 29, the Boston Pops Esplanade Orchestra will perform
at Jetties Beach to benefit the Nantucket Cottage Hospital. Peter
Nero conducts. Seats are $25 for adults, $10 for children. Call
(508) 825-8248.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION: Nantucket Chamber of Commerce (508-228-1700);
Nantucket Visitor Services and Information Bureau (508-228-0925)
can help with last-minute reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE NET: Nantucket Chamber of Commerce:
http://www.Nantucketchamber.com.
</P>
<P>
   Live camera shots of Nantucket and events information:
http://www.Nantucket.net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-10-00 1626 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000710.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nantucket Is a Summer Isle Escape  </HEADLINE>
By JEROME MINERVA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTUCKET, Mass. (AP) -- For years, the Santos-Kissam family had
vacationed in various places all over New England. When it came
time to pick a permanent summer getaway, Richard Santos and Nancy
Kissam asked their three daughters where they wanted it to be.
</P>
<P>
   The choice was unanimous -- Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a uniqueness about it. It has a huge charm,'' Santos
said, standing outside their gray-shingled house in Brant Point.
''It's absolutely matchless on a gorgeous day.''
</P>
<P>
   Most everyone who encounters the ''Faraway Island'' would
concur.
</P>
<P>
   The 3&AMP;frac12;-by-14-mile island some 30 miles out in the Atlantic off
Cape Cod has an intrinsic beauty. Herman Melville called it ''a
mere hillock, and elbow of sand; all beach, without a background.''
But upon closer examination, it's more than that. Nantucket has an
unmistakable passion for its whaling heritage, coupled with quaint
New England charm.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Martha's Vineyard can present a breathtaking view at
almost every turn, Nantucket revels in its basic, rustic, natural
state.
</P>
<P>
   And the island, from Great Point to Madaket, is not nearly as
scenic as its rival island 20 miles to the northwest. But here, it
doesn't matter. And to be sure, it hasn't stemmed the flow of
tourists in the busy summer months.
</P>
<P>
   To better understand the centuries-old tradition of Nantucket
town, a walking tour offered by the Nantucket Historical
Association is a good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   Here a town historian will guide you through just what it was
like in Nantucket's heyday when it was the whaling capital of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   No, you won't explore all 100 pre-Civil War buildings, but
enough ground is covered in the 90-minute tour for you to get a
pretty good feel for an island that was sold in 1659 for 30 English
pounds and two beaver hats.
</P>
<P>
   From the bustling Straight Wharf to the majestic Hadwen House,
the walking tour covers the volatile -- yet profitable -- years when
whale hunters set sail for the Pacific and Indian Oceans to harpoon
whales and extract from the sea giant its valuable oil to light
their lamps and lubricate their machinery.
</P>
<P>
   The tour makes note of the fire of 1846 that burned one-third of
town to the ground, paving the way for the new circa of buildings
that stand today.
</P>
<P>
   The Peter Foulger Museum plays host to the ''Essex'' exhibit,
the saga of the ill-fated whaleship Essex and its 21 crew members
in 1820. As it's told, an enraged sperm whale rammed the bow of the
Essex in the middle of the Pacific off the coast of Peru, sinking
the 238-ton vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors of the three-month ordeal detail human horrors, such
as weathering fierce storms, starvation, death and cannibalization.
The account, written by first mate Owen Chase, was the inspiration
for Melville's 1851 masterpiece ''Moby Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   When you're done taking in the island's rich history, you can
set out for a little adventure yourself.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest way to tour the pork chop-shaped island is by
mo-ped. Nantucketers may loathe it, but the entire island (and
nearly every point of interest) can be covered in a day. You might
even have time to kick back, get takeout from Claudette's Lunch Box
and picnic on Siasconset Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Heading east out of town toward Siasconset on Polpis Road is
fairly uneventful (and lacks the ever-changing views of Martha's
Vineyard). Uneventful, however, until you reach the ethereal scenes
of Sankaty Head Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   The private, links-style golf course with its ocean view and
well-kept fairways remind visitors more of Scotland than New
England. Adding to the course's mystique is the Sankaty Light
House, a red-and-white beacon built in 1849. The original lens can
be seen at the Whaling Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes from the course is the former fishing village of
Siasconset, or ''Sconset.'' Codfish Park, a residential area,
boasts the most unique lay of the land. These cottages, formerly
the dwelling places of cod fishermen, are arranged in a multilayer,
checkerboard fashion overlooking the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Erosion on Siasconset Beach is among the worst on the island. In
fact, a small cottage on Beach Street went recently for $240,000,
cheap by Nantucket standards. The reason for the fire sale? Two
powerful storms in the past decade washed a row of houses into the
sea, eroding at least 100 feet of beach in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Farther to the north (en route to Great Point) is Wauwinet and
an elegant inn -- The Wauwinet. Built by two ship captains in 1876,
the inn overlooks Head of the Harbor and the peninsula of Coatue.
One gets a decidedly European feel here -- perhaps it's the croquet
lawn.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also find a friendly and professional staff -- but at a
cost. A guest bedroom starts at $330, while entrees at Topper's run
between $40 and $60. The rates are somewhat cheaper in the spring
and fall.
</P>
<P>
   The inn also offers four-wheel drive tours up to Great Point,
one of the best places to surf cast on the island. Seal sightings,
especially in the winter, are not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   If you love the beach, there's no better place to head than to
the western half of the island. Most of the island's dozen or so
beaches, from Jetties to Surfside, can be found here.
</P>
<P>
   Jetties is the best beach within walking distance of town. With
its shore on the calm Nantucket Sound, it's ideal for kids.
</P>
<P>
   At the southwest corner of the island lies Madaket Beach, the
first of the great beaches on the Atlantic, along with Cisco,
Surfside and Siasconset.
</P>
<P>
   South out of town down Hummock Pond Road on the way to Cisco
Beach lies the best public golf course on the island, Miacomet Golf
Club.
</P>
<P>
   Further east of Cisco is Surfside Beach, but surfers prefer the
ride at Nobadeer Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is more to do on Nantucket than going
sightseeing and building sandcastles. The restaurants in town aim
to suit every palate. But even its moderately priced eateries are
high by mainland standards.
</P>
<P>
   And to be sure, there is always something going on in Nantucket.
The annual Nantucket Film Festival is held in June. The festival is
renowned for rewarding superior screenwriting while eschewing
Hollywood glitz.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the best values on the island is a 1&AMP;frac12;-hour sail
aboard the 41-foot sloop Endeavor. For $25, Capt. Jim Genthner will
put you to work raising the sail. The excursion takes you northwest
past the historic Brant Point Lighthouse, around the jetties and
out toward Eel Point. And be sure to get the crew to point out
where Tommy Hilfiger's mansion is on Nantucket Sound.
</P>
<P>
   As for anglers, they can book a private charter for $65 for 2&AMP;frac12;
hours in search of striped bass and bluefish. And if tennis is your
game, there are many clay courts.
</P>
<P>
   There are also plenty of shops, boutiques, art galleries and
antique huts lined by the cobblestone roads of Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind the summer season is short, from the end of June to
the end of August. Then comes wretched weather until the calm of
spring sets the cycle in motion again.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On The Net: Nantucket Chamber of Commerce:
http://www.Nantucketchamber.com.
</P>
<P>
   Live camera shots of Nantucket and events information:
http://www.Nantucket.net.
</P>
</TEXT>
