<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Horror Spoof Takes Box Office  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Two horror flicks were the box-office
surprises last summer. The surprise of the season so far this year
is the horror parody ''Scary Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The anything-goes gross-out comedy took in $42.3 million in its
opening weekend, the best debut ever for an R-rated movie and the
second-highest premiere this year, after ''Mission: Impossible 2.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Scary Movie,'' directed by Keenen Ivory Wayans and starring
his brothers Marlon and Shawn, also brought in more than two of
this summer's most anticipated movies did in their debuts last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   George Clooney's ''The Perfect Storm'' opened over the busy
Fourth of July weekend with $41.3 million, and Mel Gibson's ''The
Patriot'' grossed $22.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood analysts had expected ''Scary Movie'' to top the box
office this weekend but had figured its take would be in the $30
million range.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew it would be big,'' said Paul Dergarabedian, president
of Exhibitor Relations, which tracks the box office. ''I wasn't
surprised it was No. 1, but I was surprised at the sheer size of
its numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Miramax distributed the movie that pokes fun at its own
''Scream'' franchise and other horror hits such as ''The Sixth
Sense'' and ''The Blair Witch Project. Co-chairman Bob Weinstein
said Miramax and Wayans tailored the movie for the broadest
possible audience.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the movie goes beyond the 'Scream' audience,''
Weinstein said. ''Comedy is a bigger genre than horror. Everybody
wants to go to the movies and laugh. It's like Keenen said, if it
gets a laugh, it's in the movie. If it doesn't, it's out.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie borrowed one critical thing from the three ''Scream''
movies. The first ''Scream'' originally was titled ''Scary Movie,''
but Miramax felt that name sounded too much like a spoof, Weinstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wayans' movie had been titled ''Scream if You Know What I Did
Last Halloween,'' but Miramax decided to appropriate ''Scary
Movie'' because it had wider appeal, Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Since ''Scream'' in 1996, horror movies have had a resurgence.
''Scream 3'' topped the box office when it opened in February, and
last summer's horror hits included ''The Haunting'' and the
surprise blockbusters ''The Sixth Sense'' and ''Blair Witch.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It was perfect timing for 'Scary Movie,''' said Robert
Bucksbaum, a film analyst for Reel Source Inc. ''In the last few
years, we've seen just about everything we can in the horror genre,
and along comes a film that pokes fun at that and the whole
genre.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
