<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 11; Nasdaq Loses 42  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in a quiet session Monday as
investors traded cautiously ahead of a rush of corporate earnings
reports due out later this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 11.31 at 10,647.29,
according to preliminary calculations, while the Nasdaq composite
index slipped 42.49 at 3,980.71.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 4.39 at 1,474.51.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody is kind of waiting and watching until corporate
earnings announcements hit full stride the end of this week,'' said
Alan Ackerman, senior vice president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa, the first Dow component to report second-quarter results,
had higher-than-expected earnings. Shares of the aluminum producer
rose $2.063 to $29.688.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo!, expected to release its earnings report on Tuesday, fell
$6.50 to $110.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were still digesting a positive jobs report from the
government on Friday. The report gave the latest evidence that the
U.S. economy is slowing in response to the Federal Reserve's six
interest rate increases since last June.
</P>
<P>
   A slowing economy signals steadier interest rates but also the
potential for weaker corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists now expect the Fed to leave rates unchanged for
the next few months. While that's good news for investors who were
unnerved earlier this year by the Fed's actions, there is still a
great deal of concern in the market that the cumulative effect of
the rate hikes will be a drop in corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Monday's announcement by JDS Uniphase, a big
fiber-optics company, that it was buying rival SDL for $41 billion,
sent JDS tumbling $15.063, or 13 percent to $101.125. SDL rose
$25.375, or 9 percent, to $320.689.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential Securities upgraded its rating on several downtrodden
retailers, and that sent Best Buy climbing $3.375 to $74.125 and
Circuit City rising $3 to $38.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers upgraded its rating of computer chip maker
Applied MicroDevices, which rose $2.25 to $84.25.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a five to three margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 851.70 million
shares, down from Friday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 2.59 to 530.81.
</P>
<P>
   In overseas trading, the Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1
percent, Germany's DAX index was up 0.26 percent, Britain's FT-SE
100 was down 0.48 percent, and France's CAC-40 fell 1.20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
