<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Killer pleads in murders of Holocaust survivor and her caretaker  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAYS LANDING, N.J. (AP) - A man pleaded guilty Monday to beating
two women to death in a burglary that netted only a broken VCR.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Crumpton, 37, who was described by one detective as a
''one-man crime wave,'' faces consecutive life prison terms -
altogether, 126 years without parole - for the slayings of
Holocaust survivor Dora Birnbaum, 86, and her live-in caretaker,
Beatrice Cabarrus, 84, of Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had planned to seek the death penalty against
Crumpton when his trial began next month. But he slit one of his
wrists last week in a suicide attempt and then told his lawyers he
wanted to plead guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The state agreed because the plea spared family members the
ordeal of a trial while ensuring that Crumpton would die in prison,
First Assistant Atlantic County Prosecutor Murray Talasnik said.
</P>
<P>
   In court Monday, the thickly muscled Crumpton stood solemnly,
giving one-word answers to all but one question posed to him by
Superior Court Judge Manuel Greenberg and defense attorney John
Bjorklund.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he broke in, he said: ''Burglarize the place.''
</P>
<P>
   The 4-foot-9-inch, 100-pound Birnbaum was a native of Slonim,
Poland, who fled the Nazi occupation as a young woman, hiding in
woods near her village.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband and 3-year-old daughter were captured and killed by
Nazis, but she survived, married again and later moved to the
United States, where she raised a family.
</P>
<P>
   Her family hired Cabarrus to look after her in 1988. By Nov. 19,
1998, when Crumpton broke into her first-floor apartment at 311
Oriental Ave., she was too weak to get off her couch by herself.
</P>
<P>
   Crumpton told authorities he ''lost it'' after breaking in and
proceeded to bludgeon the women.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum died at the scene after choking on her own blood.
Cabarrus was beaten into a coma and died four months later, of
oxygen deprivation to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Crumpton, already a suspect in a series of similar burglaries in
the neighborhood, got only a VCR that never worked after being
bought at a yard sale by Birnbaum's son.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a one-man crime wave, all by himself,'' said a former
police detective who investigated Crumpton but has since retired.
He would not give his name.
</P>
<P>
   Under his plea to two counts of felony murder, pending charges
against Crumpton from other burglaries will be dismissed.
Sentencing was set for Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum's son, Charles Birnbaum, 53, of Hammonton, watched
Crumpton's court appearance from a gallery seat. He was accompanied
by Dorthea Joyce, 49, of Atlantic City, a neighbor who found the
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a relief to not have to go through the trial process and
open up a lot of wounds,'' he said. ''But that doesn't bring back
my mother, and it doesn't bring back Beatrice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-10-00 1646 </TRAILER>
