<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irvington cop gets 10 months for 'riding shotgun' for drug dealers  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - An Irvington police officer was sentenced
Monday to 10 months in prison by a judge who rejected a government
motion that could have kept the disgraced cop from serving jail
time.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Jeffrey Clark said the officer, Wendell
Huggins, cooperated with investigators when his crimes came to
light.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the cooperation was certified in a letter to the
judge that remains sealed, Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperation allows U.S. District Judge William H. Walls to give
a lesser sentence than the guidelines for a crime. Huggins faced
six to 12 months under the guidelines, and his lawyer, Anthony J.
Fusco Jr., asked for no jail time.
</P>
<P>
   Walls sternly refused.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not believe ... that this defendant should be, in effect,
applauded for violating his oath of office,'' Walls said. ''For me
to slap him on the wrist, as the government would have me do, I
simply will not do.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He is a police officer. He, in effect, rode shotgun for a drug
dealer,'' Walls said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he would have given Huggins a reduced sentence if
the officer had faced a term longer than six to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Walls also ordered Huggins to pay a $2,500 fine and repay $1,000
to prosecutors. He said he received that sum from drug dealers on
four trips in which he helped transport illegal drugs and money
from drug sales.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted providing protection against police interference
from November 1998 to February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins, an officer for 10 years, is to surrender within 30 days
and is ineligible for parole. He was suspended without pay earlier
this year. Fusco said Hugins would resign and lose his pension.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins, 35, pleaded guilty in February on a single charge of
obstructing interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   His assistance to drug dealers operating in Essex County was
uncovered by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to Huggins, agents were taping conversations he had had
with at least one unnamed dealer, and watched Huggins drive a
dealer and pick up packages believed to contain drugs on several
occasions, according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   During one trip, on Feb. 18, 1999, Huggins and an unnamed person
discuss transporting heroin to other locations where it could fetch
a higher price, according to court papers filed by the FBI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-10-00 1703 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000710.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Comptroller, Pataki administration keep up sniping  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state inspector general's office keeps
poor track of official cars and doesn't put out annual reports,
state Comptroller H. Carl McCall said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusually sharp response to a McCall audit, the inspector
general's office fired back that the comptroller played up minor
problems because he was thwarted in proving an alleged
preconception, namely that the inspector general's office ''had
engaged in misconduct by ignoring serious complaints of
corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall's auditors were ''forced to admit that there exists not a
shred of evidence to support any of the allegations,'' the
inspector general's office said.
</P>
<P>
   It was another aggressive response by the Republican Pataki
administration to an audit or a report from the Democratic
comptroller. McCall is thinking about running for governor in 2002,
when he could well face Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   McCall has insisted that political ambitions do not play a part
in what programs and agencies his office audits.
</P>
<P>
   The state inspector general's office is headed by Roslynn
Mauskopf and is in charge of investigating fraud, waste and
corruption in the executive branch of state government.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said his auditors found some inspector general
investigations dragged on too long, that the office had poor
controls over how its 35 vehicles for staffers were being used and
did not produce an annual report on how many cases it had opened,
investigated or closed in a given calendar year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, McCall said, his auditors were surprised at finding
staff at the inspector general's office ''so resistant'' to having
their books examined.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's office countered that ''wholesale
access'' to its files about former and ongoing investigations would
''jeopardize the lives and safety of whistleblowers, witnesses and
investigators.'' Some materials were properly shielded from
McCall's auditors for security reasons, they argued.
</P>
<P>
   Mauskopf's office also said it was unfair of McCall, who knew
about the security concerns, to suggest that the inspector general
was stonewalling the comptroller's auditors. A deal was worked out
more than a year ago under which the inspector general would
withhold sensitive documents but not the fiduciary-related papers
McCall's auditors were seeking to review, inspector general's
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Mauskopf complained Monday because McCall portrayed those
limitations on seeing sensitive materials as Mauskopf and her aides
putting a ''condition'' on the release of information to McCall.
</P>
<P>
   McCall spokeswoman Theresa Bourgeois said correcting some of the
problems, such as with oversight over use of the inspector
general's vehicles, was delayed due to the resistance McCall's
auditors got from Mauskopf's staff.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's office also got in barbs at McCall's
office for taking ''baseless and irresponsible press leaks'' and
trying to build an audit around them. At the time the audit began
in 1998, the New York Post was reporting that McCall's auditors
were exasperated that the inspector general was not doing more with
the possible malfeasance they were unearthing among state
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Mauskopf's predecessor, George Moresco, also accused Mauskopf in
the Post of socializing too much with Gov. George Pataki's inner
circle and of not maintaining the distance from the administration
Moresco said is necessary to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Mauskopf's office said a public registry of all the inspector
general's cases and all investigative activities is on file at her
office for public review. The inspector general also said its
auto-use policies adhere to state laws and that the effectiveness
or success of an investigation cannot be judged by how long they
take to conclude.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
