<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Victim of concrete attack says assailant was once a troubled child  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - An aspiring social worker bashed in the head
with a 5-pound concrete block was upbeat about her recovery Monday
and said the man who hit her was likely once a troubled child.
</P>
<P>
   ''This attack made me feel that the guy who attacked me, 20
years ago was probably a struggling kid,'' said Tiffany Goldberg,
who hopes to help disturbed children after attending graduate
school in social work at Columbia University in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   No suspect was in custody as of Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It was at least the third similar assault in New York during the
past year. Goldberg said that Nicole Barrett, who was hit with a
paving brick in November, has e-mailed her get-well wishes from
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, who was attacked Sunday as she left a Manhattan church
where she sings in the choir, was interviewed by The Associated
Press in her room at Bellevue Hospital, appearing upbeat, even
refusing an offer of hospital food with a grimace.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old native of Madison, Wis., had a black eye, a
bruise on her chin, a fracture in the back of her skull and two
chipped front teeth - but said she was grateful that her injuries
were not worse. Goldberg was released from the hospital late Monday
afternoon and said she would be staying with friends in the city.
</P>
<P>
   She told her ''two sets of parents'' - her biological parents
divorced when she was a baby and have remarried - that her injuries
were not serious enough for them to come from Wisconsin. Goldberg
told them her injuries were similar to wounds that might be
sustained if she had banged her head in a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a very cup-half-full situation,'' she said. ''If he
would have been a little mightier or struck me in a different way I
might have been more seriously hurt or even killed.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she does not remember feeling the block of concrete hit
her head.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who visited Goldberg on Monday, called
her ''a very brave young woman.'' He added, ''The police are doing
everything they can to find the person who did this.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg, a 1996 graduate of elite Sarah Lawrence College in
Westchester County, works as a waitress at the trendy Bryant Park
Grill in Manhattan. She has lived in New York City since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   She has been described by friends as a talented singer who has
appeared in small-scale productions. Goldberg said that she's not
aiming to become a Broadway star - although ''if the opportunity
occurred I would take it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said Goldberg had just left Marble Collegiate
Presbyterian Church on 29th Street and Park Avenue, where she sings
in the gospel choir, when a man hit her, tried to snatch her purse
and ran away.
</P>
<P>
   An off-duty firefighter, Lt. Jimmy Hurley, was driving by when
he saw Goldberg being attacked. Hurley said Monday he tried to
chase the attacker, but when he saw how badly Goldberg was
bleeding, he ran to help her, wrapping his white T-shirt around her
head, and held her hand.
</P>
<P>
   He said to her: ''I'm Jimmy. I'm a fireman.''
</P>
<P>
   And Goldberg said to him: ''Well, fireman Jimmy. Don't leave
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurley called 911, and after Goldberg had been taken to the
hospital, he rode around with police, searching unsuccessfully for
the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley visited Goldberg in the hospital and said he has a sister
the same age as her who lives in the Murray Hill neighborhood,
where the attacked occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ''It could have been her. I'm very happy to hear that she's
fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At least two people witnessed the attack and described the
assailant, a man apparently in his 30s, as disheveled.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said descriptions of the
attacker appeared to match that of a homeless man who frequents the
neighborhood; a city shelter is about two blocks away. Police began
distributing a sketch of the suspect on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Area residents said security cameras in a nearby building
captured the attack, but police would not comment on that. The
chunk of concrete, believed to be a piece of sidewalk, was found
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   In May, a 30-year-old Queens woman was hit with a brick and
robbed.
</P>
<P>
   And last November, Barrett, then 27, was hit on the head with a
paving brick in midtown Manhattan while walking to work. She
underwent two brain operations and has returned to her family's
home in Athens, Texas, for rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Said Goldberg: ''I felt that attack was random, just like this
attack on me.''
</P>
<P>
   But she also said this of both attacks: ''I thought it was
pretty strange - like lightning strike twice in the same place.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, who spent three days in a coma after her attack, was
shocked and saddened to hear of yet another rock assault in the
city, said her mother, Sharon Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   Paris Drake, an ex-convict and drug abuser, has pleaded innocent
to second-degree attempted murder, first-degree assault and
criminal possession of a weapon in connection with Barrett's
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Drake's lawyer, Louis Zayas, said his client was mistakenly
arrested. He cited the similarities among the three attacks and the
matching physical descriptions of the man who attacked Drake and
Goldberg as evidence that Barrett's attacker is still at large.
</P>
<P>
   But Safir said the two attacks do not appear related. ''At this
point we have no reason or evidence to believe this attack has a
connection whatsoever to Nicole Barrett or any other case,'' he
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg said the attack has not changed her mind about living
in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ''I still feel safe here,'' she said. ''My parents have never
objected to me living in New York City.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
