<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aaron to Rocker: Just Be Quiet  </HEADLINE>
By TOM SALADINO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Jermaine Dye had a bit of a fright Monday during
his first visit to Atlanta for Tuesday night's All-Star game since
the Braves traded him away four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old outfielder with the Kansas City Royals, who was
voted onto the American League team by the fans, said the
commercial jet was getting ready to land at Hartsfield Atlanta
International Airport when the plane suddenly went back into the
air and circled several times before landing without incident.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were about 50 feet off the ground, basically getting ready
to land when the plane took off into the air again. It was kinda
scary,'' said Dye, who made the squad by hitting .319 with 22 home
runs and 65 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Dye, who homered on his first major-league swing on May 17,
1996, with the Atlanta Braves, has a career batting average of .279
with 72 homers and 265 RBIs in 470 games.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   LAWTON'S DREAM: A year ago, Minnesota Twins outfielder Matt
Lawton was wondering if his career might be over after getting hit
in the face with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   He answered that question by making it to Atlanta for Tuesday
night's All-Star game as a reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last year at this time I was rehabbing in Fort Myers, Fla.,
thinking if I was ever going to get my confidence back to play the
game of baseball again,'' Lawton said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton was struck with the pitch June 9 and spent a month on the
disabled list with multiple fractures in his right eye socket.
</P>
<P>
   He came back but managed to end the season with a .259 average
and only seven home runs, after hitting 21 homers in 1998. He said
he went into the offseason with a renewed focus, though he never
dreamed about being an All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   A-ROD'S KNEE: Seattle shortstop Alex Rodriguez, voted onto the
AL All-Star team, won't play because of an injury Friday night
against the Los Angeles Dodgers while trying to break up a double
play.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez sustained a concussion when the knee of Los Angeles
shortstop Alex Cora struck him in the head, but he also twisted his
right knee, which was a bigger concern.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who came to Atlanta and took part in player
interviews, said he feels fine.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm walking around almost without a limp. I have
flexibility,'' said Rodriguez, who resisted taking an MRI.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whenever they take those MRI's, they tend to find things that
no one else can see, so I'm trying to stay away from them MRI
machines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said he expects to be back in the lineup by Saturday
or Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   MADDUX OK: Greg Maddux, selected as one of the 10 pitchers for
the NL squad, was hit by a line drive on the top of his right
shoulder during batting practice Saturday in Boston and will miss
the game. He will dress and take part in all the All-Star
festivities, including shagging fly balls before Tuesday night's
game.
</P>
<P>
   No, he won't be wearing a football helmet or shoulder pads.
''Just my glove,'' he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's Danny Graves replaced Maddux for the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta right-hander, 10-3 with a 3.32 ERA, said he felt
much better and thought he might be able to start Thursday when the
Braves travel to Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux missed his scheduled start Sunday in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just a bruise,'' Maddux said. ''It happened two days ago
and it's starting to feel a lot better. I should be ready by
Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   NO THOMAS: Despite hitting over .300 with 26 homers and 75
RBIs, Chicago White Sox slugger Frank Thomas was left off the team.
AL manager Joe Torre said Thomas had been used as a DH most of the
season, playing little first base, and he had to choose between
Thomas and Edgar Martinez of Seattle, who also is a DH.
</P>
<P>
   The DH is not used because the game is played in an NL park.
</P>
<P>
   ''Edgar Martinez's numbers are so glaring that he needs to be on
the team,'' Torre said. Martinez is hitting .354 and leads the
league in RBIs with 87.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said leaving Thomas off wasn't done ''because I don't
respect what he's done and what he's done in the past and this
year. First base is very difficult. And he has been DHing most of
the time. We don't have a DH this year.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   STAR STUFF: AL starting second baseman Roberto Alomar of the
Cleveland Indians, whose right elbow was badly swollen after being
hit by a pitch Sunday, said Monday it felt much better and the
swelling had just about disappeared, although the imprint of the
seam of a baseball where it struck him was clearly visible. ''It'll
probably be a game-time decision,'' he said about starting and
playing. ... In the hometown of Coca-Cola, free Pepsi was being
dispensed Tuesday outside Turner Field, where the temperature was
in the mid-90s. Pepsi, not Coke, is an official sponsor of major
league baseball.
</P>
</TEXT>
