<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amtrak critic resigns from oversight council  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - A leading critic of Amtrak resigned Monday
from a panel that oversees the national railway, accusing Amtrak
officials of stonewalling requests for information on its financial
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Vranich, who once was an Amtrak spokesman, also alleged
the railway is adding ''pork-barrel trains to the districts or home
towns of politically connected officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Vranich resigned from the Amtrak Reform Council, an independent
watchdog panel, but directed his complaints at the railway.
</P>
<P>
   Vranich said Amtrak ''disguises the nature and extent of its
losses through bogus accounting methods'' and refused to provide
the council with information about the cost of starting new freight
services and details on labor productivity.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Amtrak has not been honest about the fiscal
implications of delays in the start of high-speed ''Acela Express''
service between Boston and Washington, D.C. The service, originally
scheduled to begin at the end of 1999, has been delayed until at
least August because of design and testing problems.
</P>
<P>
   Citing two new routes in the home state of Wisconsin Gov. Tommy
Thompson, chairman of Amtrak's governing board, Vranich said Amtrak
is adding trains that are slow, unattractive or designed to appease
politicians rather than improve service.
</P>
<P>
   ''This so-called market-based network analysis is one huge
boondoggle,'' Vranich said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Jewell, a spokesman for Thompson, called Vranich's
accusation ''absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Governor Thompson and the other members of the board are
committed to turning Amtrak around - apparently unlike Mr. Vranich,
who throws his hands up the air and throws pot shots on his way out
the door,'' Jewell said.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak spokesman Bill Schulz said Vranich proved himself unable
to be objective about Amtrak, so ''it's probably best for the ARC
that he is no longer with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak Reform Council Chairman Gil Carmichael said he shares
some of Vranich's frustrations but does not believe the council's
work has been impaired.
</P>
<P>
   Congress created the council in 1997, when it gave Amtrak five
years to wean itself from annual federal operating subsidies. The
council's mission is to keep track of the railroad's progress
toward self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the council released an initial report questioning
some of Amtrak's accounting methods. Amtrak maintained that some
costs, like equipment depreciation, should not be counted against
its bottom line because the government pays for them.
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael said the council will continue to be independent but
supportive of Amtrak.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope Amtrak will reach self-sufficiency by 2002, and as long
as I'm chairman, I'm going to give them every benefit of the doubt
in order to make it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vranich is the fourth person to resign from the 11-person
council since its formation in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman, appointed by former House
Speaker Newt Gingrich as the panel's first chairperson, resigned
after a few months to protest Congress' refusal to let the panel
hire its own consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Monin, a labor union representative, resigned his seat
earlier this year, as did Democratic consultant Donald Sweitzer.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.amtrak.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-10-00 1731 </TRAILER>
