<DOCNO> APW20000710.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Seeks 'Heritage' Control  </HEADLINE>
By MARCELO BALLVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- As foreign cosmetic and drug
companies race to exploit the biological riches of the Amazon,
Brazil is belatedly taking steps to protect what it calls the
country's ''genetic heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a decree the government issued in late June, a new council
linked to the office of President Fernando Henrique Cardoso must
approve all research and commercial use of ''biological material''
-- every living thing in Brazil, from trees to bacteria. Foreign
companies must share any royalties from the marketing of natural
resources with the government and local institutions. Those that
violate the decree face stiff fines.
</P>
<P>
   The new decree is about more than environmental protection: It's
also about money.
</P>
<P>
   The Amazon rainforest spreads over 2 million square miles and
contains an abundance of animal and plant species. Pharmaceutical
and cosmetic companies see it as a cornucopia of everything from
new perfume fragrances to antibiotics and disease cures, and
Brazil's government wants to make sure it gets a piece of the
action.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was nothing, no regulating mechanism before this, and we
needed it to prevent controversies about research agreements,''
said Ana Cristina Kauffman, spokeswoman for Bioamazonia, a research
group created by the government last year to focus on Amazon
development.
</P>
<P>
   The government decree was a reaction to criticism of a recent
agreement between Bioamazonia and Novartis Pharma AG, a Swiss
pharmaceutical company. The deal allowed the Swiss company to
develop drugs from up to 10,000 samples of fungi and bacteria
collected in the Amazon rainforest.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also allowed them to take samples out of the
country, an accord that now will be reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and politicians said Bioamazonia, which is
linked to the government but operates independently, was selling
off genetic wealth. They complained that the Swiss company was
allowed to develop its drugs without the participation of Brazilian
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman said that before the decree was issued, Novartis Pharma
agreed to pay $4 million to Bioamazonia and share 1 percent of
royalties from any drugs developed, though the patents would remain
in Brazilian hands. That deal is now suspended while a Bioamazonia
internal committee reevaluates it.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups, meanwhile, are complaining about the
decree: They say the government now has virtually total control
over commercial use of the Amazon, leaving ecologists and Indian
groups out of the decision-making. Critics fear the new council
will be controlled by political and commercial interests.
</P>
<P>
   ''The presidential decree disregards years of debate on the
issue in the congress and in society,'' said a joint statement
signed by private environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   Nilo Diniz, a spokesman for Sen. Marina Silva, an Amazon native,
said the decree allows the council to authorize the commercial
exploration of biological resources on Indian lands without their
consent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Indians should have the right to decide what is done with
their own property,'' Diniz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-10-00 1734 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000710.0127 </DOCNO>
