<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scheduling of former porn star's extradition hearing delayed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   VANCOUVER (AP) - Former X-rated film star Kathryn Gannon, wanted
in the United States on insider trading charges, will wait two more
weeks to learn the date of her extradition hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Gannon, 31, appeared briefly in a Vancouver court on Monday as
her lawyer asked for a delay in setting the date for the hearing on
whether she will be sent to New York to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Patrick Dohm agreed to the request for more time and
scheduled a July 25 court appearance to determine when the
extradition hearing would begin.
</P>
<P>
   Gannon, known as ''Marylin Star'' in X-rated movies and
publications, was arrested in May in the lobby of her Vancouver
residence. She is free on $33,800 bail with travel restrictions,
but received permission Monday to go to Alberta for personal
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Gannon was charged in December along with James McDermott Jr.,
the former chief executive officer at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods, a
firm that specialized in bank mergers.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott was convicted in April of securities fraud for giving
Gannon inside information, prompting her to allegedly buy six
stocks illegally. She was accused of then giving the information to
a third defendant, Anthony Pomponio, who also was convicted in the
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Both men were having extramarital affairs with Gannon at the
time, lawyers in the case have said.
</P>
<P>
   Pomponio and Gannon allegedly made $170,000 in illegal profits.
</P>
<P>
   Gannon, a Canadian citizen, was arrested by the Royal Canadian
Mounted Police commercial crimes section in compliance with an
extradition request from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, she could face up to 10 years in prison on the
most serious insider trading charges.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott, 48, and Pomponio, 45, are scheduled to be sentenced
July 17. Each could get up to 10 years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-10-00 1738 </TRAILER>
