<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jets Sign Ellis, Abraham  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- The New York Jets signed defensive end
Shaun Ellis and linebacker John Abraham, the first two of the
team's unprecedented four first-round draft picks, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, from Tennessee, and Abraham, from South Carolina, were
selected 12th and 13th overall in April. Both will be in uniform
for the team's first training camp workout Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, 6-foot-5, 280 pounds, signed a five-year deal worth
$8.175 million. He received a $2.175 million bonus and the third
and fourth years of the deal are guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   In his rookie season, Ellis will have a base salary of $800,000.
That will escalate to $975,000 in 2001, $1.175 million in 2002,
$1.375 million in 2003 and $1.575 million in 2004. He also has
$100,000 worth of workout bonuses through the life of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham, who like Ellis is expected to boost the Jets' weak pass
rush, received a $7.055 million five-year contract, with a $2
million signing bonus. His base salary for this season is $740,000,
and Abraham will earn $900,000 next year, then $1,085 million,
$1.275 million and $1.455 million. Like Ellis, Abraham has $100,000
worth of workout bonuses in the deal and is 2002 and 2003 salaries
are guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ''With Shaun and John, we have explosive players who add a lot
to our defense,'' coach Al Groh said. ''They both have the ability
to get after the quarterback and they possess the size, which is
important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Anthony Becht of West Virginia, drafted 27th overall,
signed in May. New York's only unsigned rookie is 18th overall
selection Chad Pennington of Marshall, rated the top quarterback in
the draft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
