<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bartow Retires As UAB Athletic Dir.  </HEADLINE>
By JAY REEVES
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- Gene Bartow retired as UAB's athletic
director Monday, fighting back tears as he announced his decision
at the basketball arena named after him.
</P>
<P>
   ''While there's no good time for something like this, I have
concluded that it's indeed time,'' said Bartow, wearing a tie in
the school colors of green and gold.
</P>
<P>
   The 69-year-old Bartow built UAB's basketball program from
scratch in 1977 after coaching at Memphis State and following John
Wooden at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ''He got it all off and running,'' university president Ann
Reynolds said. ''He is our movie star. Everyone has heard of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartow held the dual role of basketball coach and athletic
director for 18 years. He turned over the job of basketball coach
to his son, Murry, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As athletic director, Bartow led the way as UAB was transformed
from a 10-year-old urban campus with no sports program to a
Division I-A member of Conference USA.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds hopes to hire Bartow's successor by the time his
retirement takes effect Aug. 31. Football coach Watson Brown wants
the next AD to be a lot like Bartow.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just want to see through some of the things he
envisioned,'' said Brown, hired by Bartow in 1995 to lead the
football program, which started as a club team 11 years ago and is
now Division I-A.
</P>
<P>
   Bartow led UCLA to the Final Four in 1976, the year after Wooden
retired. He was hired by UAB the next year to construct a
basketball program where none existed.
</P>
<P>
   UAB made it to the NCAA round of 16 in 1980, its second season
with a team. Bartow led the Blazers to the final eight the next
year with a record of 25-6, his best season at UAB.
</P>
<P>
   Bartow plans to keep his home in Birmingham, but he may spend
time in San Diego or Memphis, where he led Memphis State to the
Final Four in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't really have a thing, but I'm really not ready to quit
working,'' he said. ''I (just) think it's time for somebody younger
and more energetic here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-10-00 1742 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000710.0131 </DOCNO>
