<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 11; Nasdaq Loses 43  </HEADLINE>
By PHIL GALEWITZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP)-- Stocks were mixed in a quiet session Monday as
investors moved cautiously in advance of second-quarter earnings
reports that will begin in earnest later this week. High-tech
issues fell amid profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 10.60 to 10,646.58, while
the Nasdaq composite index slipped 42.91 to 3,980.29.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 3.28 to 1,475.62.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody is kind of waiting and watching until corporate
earnings announcements hit full stride the end of this week,'' said
Alan Ackerman, senior vice president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa, the first Dow component to release second-quarter
results, reported profits that were 2 cents per share above Wall
Street expectations. Investors rewarded the aluminum producer,
sending its stock up $2.063 to $29.688.
</P>
<P>
   Investors sold technology stocks after a brief run-up last week.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was some healthy profit-taking with the techs,'' said Bryan
Piskorowski, a market analyst with Prudential Securities. ''It's
earnings season now and these companies have to either put up or
shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft slipped $2.563 to $79.438 and Intel fell $1.50 to
137.813.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo!, scheduled to release its earnings on Tuesday, fell $6.50
to $110.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were still digesting a positive jobs report from the
government on Friday. The report gave the latest evidence that the
U.S. economy is slowing in response to the Federal Reserve's six
interest rate increases since last June.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists now expect the Fed to leave rates unchanged for
the next few months. While that's good news for investors who were
unnerved earlier this year by the Fed's actions, there is still a
great deal of concern in the market that the cumulative effect of
the rate hikes will mean a drop in corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers that have been battered in 2000 due to slowing sales
had a turnaround Monday after Prudential Securities upgraded its
rating on several downtrodden merchants. Best Buy rose $3.375 to
$74.125, Gap was up $2.375 to $37.875 and Home Depot gained $2.375
to $57.75.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Monday's early announcement by JDS Uniphase, a big
fiber-optics company, that it was buying rival SDL for $41 billion,
sent JDS tumbling $15.063, or 13 percent to $101.125. SDL rose
$25.375, or 9 percent, to $320.688.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers upgraded its rating of computer chip maker
Applied MicroDevices, which rose $2.125 to $84.125.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a five to three margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where composite volume came to 1.01
billion shares, down slightly from Friday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 2.61 to 530.83.
</P>
<P>
   In overseas trading, the Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1
percent, Germany's DAX index was up 0.26 percent, Britain's FT-SE
100 was down 0.48 percent, and France's CAC-40 fell 1.20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
