<DOCNO> APW20000710.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HOLD FOR RELEASE until 12:01 a.m. Tuesday  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE ROTH
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Long before the Piper Saratoga that John F.
Kennedy Jr. was piloting crashed off Martha's Vineyard on the hazy
night of July 16, 1999, Jackie Kennedy Onassis feared her son would
die in a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the latter years of her life, Jackie had a recurring
premonition that John would be killed piloting his own plane. She
pleaded with Maurice (Tempelsman, her longtime companion) to do
whatever it took to keep John from becoming a pilot,'' says a new
book, ''The Day John Died,'' which chronicles the details
surrounding the fatal accident.
</P>
<P>
   Although she encouraged her son to take chances - and he had
numerous brushes with disaster - his mother could not stand the
thought of his piloting a plane, says the book by Christopher
Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   It also says that an American Airlines passenger jet changed its
course to avoid a collision with Kennedy's plane that evening, that
Kennedy and his wife Carolyn Bessette Kennedy had worked out the
difficulties in their marriage and were ready to have a family, and
that as early as January 1997 Kennedy had expressed an interest in
running for the U.S. Senate seat being vacated by New York's Daniel
Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy did not follow through because he feared his wife might
not be able to stand the pressure of a heated political campaign,
it says.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen, whose book is being released Tuesday by publisher
William Morrow, said it is based on interviews with hundreds of
family members, friends, classmates, teachers, co-workers,
neighbors, lovers, fellow aviators and employees, as well as
photographers and journalists who covered the Kennedy family over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   It is the final chapter of his Camelot trilogy, which also
includes ''Jack and Jackie'' (1996) and ''Jackie After Jack''
(1998). It also follows his similarly framed 1998 book on Princess
Diana, ''The Day Diana Died.''
</P>
<P>
   Calls Sunday to Kennedy's cousin, Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy, and to
Sen. Ted Kennedy, the traditional spokesman for the Kennedy family,
were not immediately returned. Andersen said John's sister,
Caroline Kennedy, and the family of Carolyn Bessette Kennedy did
not agree to be interviewed for the book.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who watched the days of media coverage surrounding
Kennedy's death last year, most of the material is familiar.
</P>
<P>
   There's the flawed weather report Kennedy saw on the Internet,
indicating that the weather was good when it was not. There's pilot
Kyle Bailey, who says he was the last to see Kennedy, his wife and
her sister Lauren as they took off from Essex County Airport in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the huge shrine of flowers, cards and other gifts
left outside Kennedy's TriBeCa loft at 20 North Moore Street. And
the private star-studded funeral on Manhattan's Upper East Side,
and Caroline Kennedy's wan smile and wave to the waiting masses on
Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the book's 60 photographs, tracing John's years as a
toddler in the White House through his days as a Manhattan golden
boy and magazine founder, are also etched in the public psyche:
Little John Kennedy peeping out from under President Kennedy's desk
in the Oval Office, his famous salute at his father's funeral, the
tabloid headline ''The Hunk Flunks'' about his failed bar exam, the
1995 unveiling of his magazine, ''George,'' and the photo of
Kennedy and his ethereal bride leaving the humble Georgia church
where they were wed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main thing I want to do is to set the record straight,''
Andersen said Sunday. ''First, there have been a lot of rumors and
stories that divorce was imminent. I found absolutely no evidence
of that. They had gone through a period of crisis and were through
the other end. They were on the verge of starting a family of their
own,'' he said. ''I also found no evidence behind rumors that
Bessette had a drug problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There has been a lot of posthumous character assassination.
But I'm a warts-and-all biographer and if John had any character
flaws, I couldn't find them,'' he said. ''If anything, the surprise
was that people seemed more upset about John's death than I had
realized. More people burst into tears during interviews than you
can imagine. It is all just so painfully tragic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
