<HEADLINE> Irvington police officer gets 10 months for 'riding shotgun' for drug dealers </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - An Irvington police officer was sentenced
Monday to 10 months in prison by a judge who rejected a government
motion that could have kept the disgraced cop from serving jail
time.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Jeffrey Clark said the officer, Wendell
Huggins, cooperated with investigators when his crimes came to
light.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the cooperation was certified in a letter to the
judge that remains sealed, Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperation allows U.S. District Judge William H. Walls to give
a lesser sentence than the guidelines for a crime. Huggins faced
six to 12 months under the guidelines, and his lawyer, Anthony J.
Fusco Jr., asked for no jail time.
</P>
<P>
   Walls sternly refused.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not believe ... that this defendant should be, in effect,
applauded for violating his oath of office,'' Walls said. ''For me
to slap him on the wrist, as the government would have me do, I
simply will not do.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is a police officer. He, in effect, rode shotgun for a drug
dealer,'' Walls said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he would have given Huggins a reduced sentence if
the officer had faced a term longer than six to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Walls also ordered Huggins to pay a $2,500 fine and repay $1,000
to prosecutors. He said he received that sum from drug dealers on
four trips in which he helped transport illegal drugs and money
from drug sales.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted providing protection against police interference
from November 1998 to February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins, an officer for 10 years, is to surrender within 30 days
and is not eligible for parole. He was suspended without pay
earlier this year. Fusco said he would resign and lose his pension.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins, 35, pleaded guilty in February to a single charge of
obstructing interstate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   His assistance to drug dealers operating in Essex County was
uncovered by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to Huggins, agents were taping conversations he had with
at least one unnamed dealer, and watched Huggins drive a dealer and
pick up packages believed to contain drugs on several occasions,
according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   During one trip, on Feb. 18, 1999, Huggins and an unnamed person
discussed transporting heroin to other locations where it could
fetch a higher price, according to court papers filed by the FBI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-10-00 1826 </TRAILER>
