<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that were moving substantially or trading
heavily Monday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE
</P>
<P>
   Dole Food Co. Inc., up 12.50 cents to $15.688
</P>
<P>
   The maker of Dole juices and canned fruit posted
better-than-expected second-quarter earnings, but results were down
from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell International Inc., unchanged to $35
</P>
<P>
   The Morris Township, N.J.-based specialty chemicals and security
conglomerate is taking decisive actions to restore credibility,
said chairman and chief executive Michael Bonsignore, including
shedding 6,000 jobs. The stock took a hit recently when Honeywell
announced its second-quarter results would fall short of
expectations, but the company said Monday it is on track to meet
its reduced numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Geon Co., down $2.125 to $16.75
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland-based maker of vinyl compounds expects
second-quarter operating earnings to meet analysts' estimates. But
the company said operating results exclude charges for the closure
of an engineered films plant, the termination of a director pension
plan, and public debt financing costs.
</P>
<P>
NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
   Good Guys Inc., down 40.63 cents to $3.469
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco-based specialty retailer of consumer
entertainment electronics said it expects to report a loss for the
third quarter that is substantially lower than its $8.1 million
loss for the year-ago period. The company attributed the decline in
sales to the elimination of low-margin computers and home office
products and the de-emphasis of entry level offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Tenfold Corp., down $6.813 to $10.25
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake City-based electronic business software company
said it expects to report a second-quarter loss of 1 cent to 3
cents a share, far below analysts forecasts. The results were lower
than expected due to a longer-than-anticipated sales cycle, higher
spending and delays in some existing projects.
</P>
<P>
   Krispy Kreme Doughnuts Inc., down $6.375 to $73.125
</P>
<P>
   Barron's said the Winston-Salem, N.C. based specialty donut
maker may be overpriced. The retro-trendy donut store chain may
face slowing sales and the fickle nature of consumer palates.
</P>
</TEXT>
