<HEADLINE> Parties seek candidates as convention dates approach  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - Grousing that good candidates are hard
to find, state political leaders will meet over the next two weeks
to choose nominees for the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of seats for the state Legislature are going uncontested
or facing lackluster challenges. Party leaders in some
congressional districts are still trying to find opponents for
longtime incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats plan to hold their state convention Friday evening
at Southern Connecticut State University, to formally nominate U.S.
Sen. Joseph Lieberman to a third term.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans plan to nominate Waterbury Mayor Philip Giordano
to run against Lieberman. Their state convention is July 22 at
Sacred Heart University in Fairfield.
</P>
<P>
   A June Quinnipiac College poll did not foreshadow much sizzle in
this race: Lieberman had about a 6-to-1 advantage over Giordano for
the November election.
</P>
<P>
   If there are any fireworks at the Democrats' annual meeting, it
they will revolve around a move by some party members to bar party
Chairman Ed Marcus from a fifth term. Efforts to oust Marcus
through party bylaws have failed before.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Paindiris, a Glastonbury lawyer who helped lead former New
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley's campaign in Connecticut, is trying to
change party rules so that the chairman is elected by the delegates
at the convention, rather than by the state central committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state convention's going to be very boring except for this
rules change,'' Paindiris said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus said there will be a debate and a vote on the rule
change. He said he opposed the rule change, likening the current
system to the corporate world, where a board of directors elects
the company's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think he has very much support. I don't think there's
any reason to try to do this,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' keynote speaker will be civil rights leader and
U.S. Rep. John Lewis of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Other conventions at the local and district level will be held
over the next two weeks to put up candidates for Congress and the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Only 3rd District U.S. Rep. Rosa DeLauro, a New Haven Democrat,
is without an announced challenger.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, 2nd District Republicans nominated state Rep.
Robert Simmons of Stonington to run against U.S. Rep. Sam
Gejdenson.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP on Monday planned to anoint former Danbury Rep. Mark
Nielsen to try again to unseat U.S. Rep. Jim Maloney of the 5th
District.
</P>
<P>
   Former professional wrestler Bob Backlund was expected to get
the nod from Republicans in the 1st District to run against
one-term incumbent U.S. Rep. John Larson.
</P>
<P>
   And U.S. Rep. Chris Shays was expected to get the Republican
Party's blessing to run again for the 4th District in Fairfield
County. The Democrats are supporting Stephanie Sanchez, a former
selectwoman from Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Nancy Johnson in the 6th District will face a
challenge from Watertown Councilman Paul Valenti. Her nominating
convention is scheduled for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats plan to hold district conventions for Congress on
July 22.
</P>
<P>
   Some races in the Legislature are marked by lack of interest.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest of number of opportunities to take a seat under the
gold dome in Hartford are in Litchfield County, with the retirement
of many longtime state lawmakers including Senate Minority Leader
M. Adela Eads, R-Kent.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats were choosing state Senate candidates in district
conventions Monday. Most Republican committees planned to meet
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The most hotly contested House race is in the 36th District,
where Rep. Claire Sauer, D-Lyme, is retiring. Three Democrats and
three Republicans are vying for the seat which represents Chester,
Deep River, part of Essex, Lyme and part of Old Saybrook.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are holding a district convention Tuesday. Most
Republican committees meet July 18.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a pretty civic-minded area,'' said Ronald Phillips, vice
chairman of the Lyme Democratic Town Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
