<HEADLINE> Two stabbed in chest after crashing party  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TOMS RIVER , N.J. (AP) - Two Ocean County men were stabbed in
the chest after a group of party crashers got into a street fight
involving at least 20 people, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The fight began at about 2:15 a.m. Sunday after groups of
uninvited guests crashed a baptism party at Tommy's Restaurant,
police said. About 40 family members were in a dining hall of the
restaurant when a large group of people crashed the party,
according to police Lt. William Herkert.
</P>
<P>
   The hosts asked the party crashers to leave and the fight
erupted outside. Police said no fighting took place inside the
restaurant on Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   At least one man flashed a knife during the fight, police said.
A folding knife was recovered at the scene, but police said a
security guard hired to patrol the party described the weapon used
in the stabbings as a kitchen knife.
</P>
<P>
   The guard also told police that some of the people were throwing
beer cans at each other.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups scattered when the security guard called police.
Authorities said Monday it appears the men were stabbed after the
groups left the scene. Police said they haven't determined a motive
for the stabbings.
</P>
<P>
   One man, identified as Juan Marin, 21, of Berkeley Township, was
taken to Community Medical Center with two stab wounds to the upper
chest at 2:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The other man, Antonio Ruiz, also 21 and of Berkeley Township,
was later found by Beachwood police and taken to Jersey Shore
Medical Center in Neptune. He was found near Route 9 and Anchor
Avenue in Beachwood, about a mile from the restaurant, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Both men, who are immigrants from Mexico, were to be released
from the hospital Tuesday, police said. It isn't clear if Marin and
Ruiz know the family that was hosting the party, Herkert said.
</P>
<P>
   Herkert said police brought in an interpreter to get statements
from witnesses because many of those at the restaurant speak
Spanish. Herkert said some witnesses may be reluctant to come
forward because they may be in the United States illegally.
</P>
</TEXT>
