<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assault on family called random act of violence  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLOUCESTER TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - Guests, employees and the owner
of a motel where a woman was bound and raped, then held hostage in
a room with her children, say they're not afraid of more violence.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Ernest Buffaloe, 23, of Camden, and a 14-year-old
boy from Gloucester Township broke into a room at the Howard
Johnson Express Inn late Saturday night, raped a Blackwood woman in
front of her two sons, ages 2 and 6, then held the family hostage.
When the father returned to the room, he also was bound.
</P>
<P>
   The family escaped after about 30 minutes, but the
hostage-takers barricaded themselves in the room for three hours
before surrendering, police said. They remained incarcerated
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It could have happened anywhere,'' Rose Anne Tomasello, head
of housekeeping, said Monday. ''It just happened to happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Gentile and his wife, Anne Neeley, both of New Orleans, stay
at the motel for a few days every summer while they visit their son
and grandson in nearby Erial. They chose it because it's the
safest, cleanest inn in the area, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's spooky, isn't it?'' Neeley said while lounging by the
motel pool. ''I always feel so safe up here, compared to living in
New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   But they said news of the attack didn't make them feel in
danger.
</P>
<P>
   ''I doubt it's going to be a regular thing,'' Gentile said.
''We're pretty careful in a hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomasello said the housekeeping employees were not shaken by the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   ''They don't have any fears of someone lurking around. They're
not doing anything differently while they're cleaning the rooms,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the suspects had tried to break into at least one
other room on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Raj Parikh, who owns and operates the inn about 15 miles
southeast of Camden, said a security guard was on duty Saturday
night, as is the case every weekend night. He also said the
100-unit motel has chains, dead bolts and electronic locks on the
doors.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll just have to take extra precautions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The family, which was staying at the motel while looking for a
new place to live, had been there for about two months, Parikh
said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's break-in was the first incident to occur at the motel
on the Black Horse Pike since it opened 15 years ago, Parikh said.
He held a staff meeting Sunday to comfort his 15 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Miller, spokesman for the inn's parent company, Howard
Johnson International Inc., based in Parsippany, said the company
regrets the incident and is cooperating with law enforcement
officials in their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Buffaloe and the teen were charged with robbery, aggravated
assault, sexual assault, kidnapping, conspiracy and cruelty to a
child.
</P>
<P>
   Buffaloe is being held at the Camden County Jail. Bail had not
been set Monday, and he had not been assigned a public defender, a
jail official said.
</P>
<P>
   Buffaloe was scheduled to be arraigned July 18 in state Superior
Court in Camden, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-age suspect was taken to the Camden County Juvenile
Detention Center in Lakeland. He attended a hearing Monday morning,
at which it was determined that he should remain incarcerated, said
Gloucester Township Police Capt. Edward Smith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
