<HEADLINE> Report: Pinelands Commission members oppose Whitman appointee  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman's office confirmed it
has directed the Pinelands Commission to hire a state official who
had been passed over for the commission's top staff job.
</P>
<P>
   But some commission members oppose the idea and may press to
bring it up before the full panel for a vote, according to a report
Monday in the Philadelphia Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime staff director Terrence Moore stepped down last fall
and the commission selected Annette Barbaccia, a former
environmental official in the New York mayor's office, to replace
him effective in August.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's staff subsequently directed the commission to create a
new administrative post for Robert A. Marshall, a lawyer in the
state attorney general's office who specializes in environmental
affairs. Marshall had been one of the finalists for the post given
to Barbaccia.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper reported that several commission members opposed
hiring Marshall at a time when they cannot get funding for other
positions, and that they resented the interference from the
governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   The Pinelands Commission regulates development and land
preservation in the 1.1-million acre Pinelands National Reserve. Of
its 15 members, seven are appointed by the governor, seven by each
of the counties within the Pinelands' jurisdiction and one by the
U.S. Interior Secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Otterbourg, a spokeswoman for Whitman, said the governor
wants Marshall hired despite the opposition of some members. ''The
governor still believes the position is necessary for the Pinelands
to live up to its fullest potential,'' she said, adding Marshall is
well-qualified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
