<HEADLINE> Suspect in shotgun killing returned to NJ  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A former New Jersey man has been returned
to the Garden State to stand trial in a 1996 Mercer County shotgun
killing that occurred during a string of brothel robberies.
</P>
<P>
   Renford L. ''Gaudy'' Wilson, 23, formerly of Hamilton, was
arrested in the Bronx in April. Gov. Christie Whitman signed a
warrant Monday to have him returned to the state, Mercer County
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was identified as the triggerman in the October 29, 1996,
slaying of Leandro Rafael Garcia Hernandez, Mercer County
Prosecutor Daniel G. Giaquinto said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Wilson and three other men, Wigberto Gonzalez,
29, Roberto Flores, 23, and Kurt Richard Martin, 29, committed a
string of brothel robberies at the time Hernandez was killed. The
four encountered Hernandez at a bordello on South Cook Avenue in
Trenton during one of the robberies and Wilson shot him in the face
with a 12-gauge shotgun, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was on the run until his April 14 arrest. He was arrested
without incident.
</P>
<P>
   The three men with Wilson have already pleaded guilty in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Giaquinto said Gonzalez and Flores pleaded guilty to aggravated
manslaughter. Gonzalez faces up to 20 years in prison. Flores faces
up to 18 years. Giaquinto said Martin pleaded guilty to
manslaughter and faces up to 15 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
