<HEADLINE> Mexico's Ruling Party in Chaos  </HEADLINE>
By NIKO PRICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's defeated ruling party was forced to
shut down its headquarters Monday when peasants stormed the
sprawling complex to demand the freedom of a jailed leader and a
voice in the party's future.
</P>
<P>
   The group's leader, congressman Humberto Serrano, said his
supporters would bolt the party if the current leadership doesn't
pay more attention to grass-roots groups like his, and said Mexico
would ''heat up'' if the ruling party doesn't shed its bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Careful, very careful with the countryside,'' Serrano said.
''If the party doesn't take up the peasant causes, the workers'
causes, we're going to bury it.''
</P>
<P>
   About 150 supporters, most of clad in dirty baseball caps and
dirty T-shirts, chanted anti-PRI slogans, and one sprayed dust from
a fire extinguisher, setting off a small stampede.
</P>
<P>
   Security officials blocked off the main doors to the party
headquarters for several hours, saying ''there seems to be a
problem inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Serrano finally met with some midlevel officials, who placed a
phone call to the governor of Morelos state, where the peasants are
from. Serrano said the governor promised to free the peasant
leader, jailed in a land dispute, by Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he doesn't keep his word, if he's making fun of us, the
next time we won't tell them what time we're coming or where we'll
be. Then this will get good,'' Serrano told the crowd of
enthusiastic supporters.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was sure the governor could free the leader if he
wanted to, because ''he appointed all the judges.''
</P>
<P>
   The small protest highlighted one of the most pressing problems
for the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, which on July 2
lost its first presidential election ever. The party had held the
presidency since its formation in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly disenfranchised groups within the PRI have been
fighting for power amid the vacuum created by the loss in a party
where orders have always come straight from the president.
</P>
<P>
   A group of PRI governors and a few party officials have been
meeting to set a new agenda for the party. The two main feuding
camps are followers of Francisco Labastida, the defeated
presidential candidate, and those of Roberto Madrazo, the
charismatic southern governor who lost to Labastida in the party's
first primary in November.
</P>
<P>
   Serrano's group supports Madrazo, who argues that the PRI return
to its roots. Labastida wants to continue the reforms of recent
years, which led to a more open, democratic party -- but which have
been blamed for the loss of power.
</P>
<P>
   Serrano's supporters tore down Labastida flags that still
adorned the party headquarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-10-00 1900 </TRAILER>
