<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China PM Arrives for EU Visit  </HEADLINE>
By CONSTANT BRAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- China's prime minister paid the
first-ever visit by a Chinese leader to European Union headquarters
Monday, while his foreign minister said China would adopt U.N.
human rights treaties by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Zhu Rongji met with Belgian Prime Minister Guy
Verhofstadt and King Albert as part of a tour of European capitals
aimed largely at building economic ties between China and the
15-member EU. Meanwhile, Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan met with EU
External Relations Commissioner Chris Patten.
</P>
<P>
   Patten, who was Britain's last Hong Kong governor, was keen to
talk about China's human rights record. EU officials said Tang told
him China would seek to ratify U.N. human rights treaties aimed at
improving economic standards and social conditions such as access
to education.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu also met with Javier Solana, the EU's foreign policy
representative to discuss EU-China relations, where human rights
was the main area of concern for Solana.
</P>
<P>
   ''The disagreement on human rights should not prevent the
continuation of the political dialogue,'' Solana said after his
half-hour talk with the Chinese premier. Solana stressed the
importance of continuing communication between the two and added
that more would be done by both sides in the near future to bring
them closer together.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 demonstrators gathered outside EU headquarters to
protest against China's policies in Tibet and human rights
infringements in China.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a 1996 ''dialogue on human rights'' between the EU and
China, progress has been slow initiating reforms in China to
promote civil rights, EU officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu's 15-day tour of European capitals includes a four-day stop
in Brussels, and market opening is high on his agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Trade between the EU and China has steadily increased since
1978, totaling $51 billion in 1998. The EU has become China's
second-largest export market, and China has become the EU's
third-largest trading partner after the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   China and the EU signed an agreement in Beijing in May on
China's entry into the World Trade Organization, which sets rules
for global trade. China is moving toward joining the group next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the world trade agreement, the EU Commission -- the EU's
executive body -- still says China's markets are not open enough.
The commission is keen to see speedier market-based reforms there.
</P>
<P>
   The EU already has pledged some $57 million in cooperation
agreements aimed at reforms in many Chinese sectors, including
transportation, high technology, energy, financial services and
telecommunications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-10-00 1905 </TRAILER>
