<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NJ rabbi resigns after article reports years-old abuse allegations  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A New Jersey rabbi has resigned from a
leadership position at a prominent Jewish youth organization after
a weekly newspaper published allegations that he sexually and
physically abused several teen-agers under his care more than 20
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Baruch Lanner, 50, of Fair Lawn, left his job as director
of regions at the National Conference of Synagogue Youth last month
after the June 23 article in The Jewish Week, the nation's largest
Jewish weekly, was published, said officials with the Orthodox
Jewish youth group.
</P>
<P>
   The article quotes more than 10 men and women, now in their 30s
and 40s, who said Lanner kissed, fondled and slapped teen-age
girls, kicked boys in the groin and attacked one with a knife. They
said officials at the Orthodox Union, the New York organization
that operates the youth group, ignored repeated complaints about
Lanner's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The Orthodox Union, which has a membership of nearly 1,000
synagogues and is responsible for certifying kosher foods, began an
internal investigation of its own conduct after publication of the
article.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are terrible charges. We have to get to the bottom of
it,'' said Dr. Mandell Ganchrow, president of the Orthodox Union.
He said an independent commission would focus only on the Orthodox
Union's conduct, and not try to determine whether the charges
against Lanner are true.
</P>
<P>
   Lanner on Monday said he could not comment on the charges
against him without speaking to his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would love to talk about it, but I really can't,'' Lanner
said.
</P>
<P>
   A call to Lanner's lawyer by The Associated Press was not
returned Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's editions of The New York Times, Lanner either denied
or said he didn't recall the charges made in the article. He did
acknowledge kneeing a male student in the groin while he was a high
school principal at a school he founded in Deal.
</P>
<P>
   Lanner resigned from the Hillel school in 1997. He also had
worked as a teacher at The Frisch School, a yeshiva in Paramus.
</P>
<P>
   Lanner worked for three years as director of regions at the
youth group, planning programs and leading a six-week summer tour
of Israel for teen-age boys, said Orthodox Union spokesman David
Olivestone. He had worked at different jobs for the organization
for many years, Olivestone said.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues described him as a charming, effective speaker who
became a substitute parent to many of the teens under his care.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Yosef Blau, a counselor at Yeshiva University, sat on a
religious panel in 1989 that evaluated allegations that Lanner had
attacked a young man suffering from Hodgkin's disease with a
kitchen knife.
</P>
<P>
   The panel concluded the charges could not be proved, but Blau
said he later received many telephone calls and letters from former
students who complained that Lanner had been abusive to them. He
said he believed allegations in The Jewish Week that the
allegations were ignored by the Orthodox Union.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that they were so enamored with his success and
accomplishments that they didn't want to hear problems,'' Blau
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
