<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brackens, Jaguars at 'Impasse'  </HEADLINE>
By EDDIE PELLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- It has been a few weeks since the
Jacksonville Jaguars and Tony Brackens have talked about a new
contract. And the defensive end's agent said the sides are at a
''complete impasse.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagged as Jacksonville's franchise player, Brackens is
threatening to hold out through training camp -- maybe beyond -- if
he doesn't get a new deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he doesn't have a contract, he's not going to be in camp,''
agent Michael George said Monday. ''We're not close to having the
numbers that would translate to a final deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Camp begins next Friday, and the Jaguars must prepare as though
they will be without Brackens, who led the team with 12 sacks last
season and made his first Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   This offseason, top defensive ends are fetching contracts worth
$7 million to $8 million a year with signing bonuses of $12 million
to $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   Without a contract, Brackens could play for $4.2 million next
season as Jacksonville's franchise player.
</P>
<P>
   He could also sit out, which seems to be the most-likely option.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars senior vice president Michael Huyghue said the team
isn't in a panic situation and hopes to resume negotiations in time
for camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've reached an impasse,'' Huyghue said last week. ''We
haven't gotten past that yet. That's just the reality of the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   George said he is waiting for the team to approach him.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't negotiate against ourselves,'' he said. ''They've got
to come and sort of join us.''
</P>
<P>
   Brackens could become the first veteran holdout in the team's
short history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
