<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USDA to try to buy surplus cranberries to help growers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - The federal government has agreed to buy
30.4 million pounds of cranberry products in the coming months to
help growers who have a glut on their hands, according to a
published report.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase is intended to help save farmers from
overproduction and a steep drop in prices, The Philadelphia
Inquirer reported in Monday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture is negotiating with schools
and nutrition programs to see if they'd want cranapple juice,
cranberry sauce and trail mix with cranberries. George Chartier, a
spokesman for the USDA, said the agency would know in the next few
weeks if it can proceed with the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department last week decided to force farmers to
cut production or dump about 15 percent of their crop this fall to
winnow down the surplus and reverse the downward spiral in prices.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers across the country, including the 47 cranberry growers
in New Jersey, faced the prospect of bringing in less than $30 per
barrel this year. In 1996 a barrel sold for a high of $65.90. In
some areas, farmers are earning less than $10 per barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Under the USDA's new limits, growers will be allowed this year
to sell only 85 percent of their usual production, which means they
will have to dispose of about 884,000 barrels of fruit, enough to
make almost 40 million gallons of cranberry juice cocktail.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus is so large that processors expect to have about 4.6
million barrels of cranberries on hand in September - about 80
percent of the nation's annual production - when growers start
harvesting this year's crop.
</P>
<P>
   Growers created the problem themselves. Strong demand and high
prices in the early 1990s spurred new people to get into the
business and led existing operations to expand acreage, say
industry experts. Cranberries grow on perennial vines that don't
start producing for two to three years after they are planted.
</P>
<P>
   Demand peaked in 1994 with per capita consumption of processed
berries at 1.7 pounds. It has since declined, to 1.6 pounds in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   To increase demand, growers are considering forming a national
promotional program similar to the dairy industry's ''Got Milk?''
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey ranks third in cranberry production, behind Wisconsin
and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the production cutback, the effect on consumer prices
will be modest, the USDA said. Ocean Spray, a grower cooperative
that accounts for 70 percent of cranberry production, says it plans
to reduce prices, despite the production limit.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA's purchase program, begun by Franklin D. Roosevelt,
bought more than 1 billion pounds of commodities worth $721.5
million last year, The Inquirer reported. The agency added
cranberries to its shopping list last year when the surplus crisis
was confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA has already bought 13 million pounds of cranberry
products this year, but much of that was cranapple juice, which
doesn't have much cranberry in it, and trail mix, which contains
only about 20 percent cranberries.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: USDA's Agricultural Marketing Service:
http://www.ams.usda.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
