<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Push for China Trade Vote  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate's Democratic leader on Monday
demanded a vote this month on granting permanent trade status to
China, saying passage of the legislation could be in jeopardy if
Republicans put off action until September.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said he was ''alarmed'' that no date
had been set this month for a vote on the China trade bill. He said
he understood that Republicans were now moving toward delaying the
vote until after Congress returns from its August recess.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said he supported
the legislation that would expand and stabilize trade with China,
but would not now commit to a date for a vote. He said his first
priority this month was passing spending bills for fiscal year
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Lott acknowledged that he stated last month that he hoped to
consider the China bill before the August vacation, but ''I never
said for sure when it would be. I said it was my intent and it is
still my intent.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a major hurdle to setting a date for the trade bill was
Democratic objections to taking up a parallel bill, offered by
Sens. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., and Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., that
would require annual assessments of China's weapons proliferation
records and give the president the authority to impose sanctions if
China breaks nonproliferation agreements.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would ''feel much freer to go ahead'' with the trade
bill if Democrats agreed to vote first on Thompson-Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, citing recent reports of China's aiding Pakistan's
missile program, said his bill was needed because ''the Chinese are
basically telling us to get lost. We know what they are doing and
they are apparently not even denying it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has agreed to separate consideration of his bill so
that it will not complicate final passage of the trade bill, which
the House passed in May by a 237-197 vote. But he has indicated he
would offer his measure as an amendment to the trade bill if he
does not get a separate vote.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, in turn, say the Thompson measure should not be
considered before Lott sets a July date for taking up the trade
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said that without an agreement on the trade bill he
would go to the Senate floor this week with a motion to take it up
this month. ''We cannot fail to act on that issue any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade bill has the strong backing of business and
agriculture groups that have strong ties to the Republican Party.
U.S. Chamber of Commerce President Thomas Donohue, in an op-ed
piece in the Washington Post Monday, urged the Senate to reject the
Thompson-Torricelli measure because, he said, unilateral sanctions
never work. He urged passage of the permanent trade status
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott denied that he was under pressure from GOP backers for
quick action. ''Why don't I know anything about it?'' he asked,
saying that during the weeklong July 4th recess he got only one
call urging him to move on the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The China trade bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
