<BODY>
<HEADLINE> REPORTER'S NOTEBOOK: Clinton, Paterno have friendly encounter at Penn State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) - President Clinton's face lit up when
he encountered Penn State football coach Joe Paterno in the
audience after addressing the National Governors' Association near
the university's campus Monday.
</P>
<P>
   There's a family angle to the connection between the two men.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton's father, Hugh Rodham, was a former Penn
State player, and a big booster of the Nittany Lions before he died
in 1993, Paterno explained after the two men chatted. Her brother,
Hugh Jr., was a walk-on player in the late '60s or early '70s,
Paterno said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The family was really good to me when I was a young coach, her
father in particular,'' Paterno, a Republican, said of the Rodhams.
''Her father helped us when we tried to recruit some kids out of
Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton circulated among the governors and VIPs, chatting with
New Jersey's Christie Whitman, patting Pennsylvania's Tom Ridge on
the back twice, and embracing actor and director Rob Reiner.
</P>
<P>
   He lingered at a doorway to shake hands and pose for pictures
before exiting the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   ''You and I could go into business,'' Clinton joked with one man
who snapped a picture of him with a conference participant. ''I
could arrange the pictures and you could flash them.''
</P>
<P>
   Major corporations handed their wish lists to the nation's
governors Monday, calling for a reduction in state regulation and
more business-friendly policies.
</P>
<P>
   Syndicated political columnist David Broder of The Washington
Post held each of the corporate officials to three-minute
summations in his role as moderator of a panel discussion that
sought to define the term ''new economy'' that was used liberally
throughout the 3&AMP;frac12;-day National Governors' Association annual
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Stone of The Boeing Co. said states must recognize the
importance to businesses of ''meat-and-potato-type issues,'' such
as unemployment taxes and Workers' Compensation premiums.
</P>
<P>
   ''State to state, the cost of doing business is very important''
in where corporations create jobs, Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Wood of the Prudential insurance company urged governors to
''educate'' regulators and legislators who are less sensitive to
the needs of business.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governors get it,'' said Fred Hoffman of DaimlerChrysler
Corp., echoing other corporate panelists who complimented the
governors for their pro-business views.
</P>
<P>
   ''Enough flattery,'' Broder said with a smile. ''Move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the corporations represented in the panel discussion are
among the NGA's ''corporate fellows,'' which provide financial
support for the organization as well as information about
governmental issues that affect them.
</P>
<P>
   A committee of governors touted their states' programs in a
broad-brush committee session on aiding the disadvantaged Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jim Hunt of North Carolina said his state is providing $330
million to programs for children, including efforts to provide
child care in regions where it is tough to get.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware's Tom Carper spoke of a program that places inmates who
need such services as drug and alcohol counseling into close-knit
units where they can get support from each other.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman said she consolidated services for older
New Jerseyans into one department where there used to be four.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey has also instituted a toll-free telephone line where
senior citizens can call to get knowledgeable answers on a broad
range of matters. In keeping with the preferences of many older
people, the line is answered by state workers and not a recording,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin has provided money to help disabled people get
mortgages, Gov. Tommy G. Thompson said. Less than 5 percent of
those with disabilities own their own homes, Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-member Democratic Governors' Association on Monday placed
Maryland Gov. Parris N. Glendening in line to become the group's
chairman in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Glendening will begin a one-year term as chairman of
the bipartisan National Governors' Association, which is winding up
its annual meeting in State College, Pa. He will take the helm of
the Democratic governors' group at the beginning of 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
