<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UW Probes Alleged Players' Benefits  </HEADLINE>
By JR ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Wisconsin athletes who bought merchandise
for unadvertised discounts at a shoe store owned by a school
booster did so without knowledge that it could violate NCAA rules.
</P>
<P>
   The university notified the NCAA of the possible violations and
began its own investigation after reports surfaced that members of
the football and men's basketball teams may have received special
credit arrangements at The Shoe Box not available to other clients.
</P>
<P>
   The school also is probing allegations that some of them may
have exchanged university-issued shoes for merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Associate athletic director Vince Sweeney said Monday the
university has not determined whether the purchases constitute a
rules violation, though the athletes did not knowingly violate NCAA
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would argue, at least at this point, that if it turns out
what we think it will be, if it is indeed a violation, it was
inadvertent in nature and thus secondary,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA defines a secondary violation as ''one that provides
only a limited recruiting or competitive advantage and that is
isolated or inadvertent in nature.''
</P>
<P>
   A report in the Wisconsin State Journal detailed purchases by
eight members of the Badgers' Final Four men's basketball team and
14 players from the Rose Bowl champion football team. The paper
reported players received discounts of 25 to 40 percent and
interest-free credit.
</P>
<P>
   Among the players listed were Heisman Trophy winner Ron Dayne,
starting quarterback Brooks Bollinger, and all five starters from
the basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Shoe Box owner Steve Schmitt dismissed the allegations as the
grumblings of a fired former employee and insisted he gives similar
discounts to an array of customers, not just athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Schmitt, who holds men's basketball season tickets and has
donated money to the university in the past, said he has no
personal relationship with athletes outside of selling them shoes
and merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   The university's compliance officer visited Schmitt's store in
November after hearing rumors that players were receiving special
treatment there. Schmitt said the visit was very casual and the
university sent him a thank you letter afterward for his
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney said the university visited Schmitt to make sure he
understood the NCAA rules on boosters' relationships with players
but didn't know the extent of what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the time, I thought we did above and beyond what we would
normally do with rumors,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   If the purchases constitute a rules violation, it would be the
third time in the last decade the university broke NCAA rules.
</P>
<P>
   The wrestling program was put on probation in 1994 for improper
use of booster funds that included impermissible benefits to
athletes, a major rules violation.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the NCAA found the athletic department had committed
a major rules infraction because coaches and staff members received
reimbursement for expenses from a boosters fund without approval
from the chancellor. That probation was scheduled to end in
November.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA spokeswoman Jane Jankowski said the NCAA would not comment
on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-10-00 2044 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000710.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Eyes Cheaper Drug Imports  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amid growing public resentment of high
prescription drug prices, the House late Monday debated whether to
prevent the government from discouraging the purchase of drugs in
Canada or other countries.
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number of Americans have been going to Canada,
Mexico and other countries to purchase prescription drugs cheaper
than what they cost in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Technically it's illegal to import prescription drugs, and the
Food and Drug Administration sometimes has send warning letters to
people caught doing it.
</P>
<P>
   The House considered late Monday whether to put an amendment
onto an FDA appropriations bill that would prevent the agency from
enforcing the law or mailing such warning letters.
</P>
<P>
   ''People's lives are being shortened today because of the
abnormally high and ridiculously increased price of
prescriptions,'' said Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Because of cost controls, drugs can cost several times less in
Canada, Mexico and Europe than in the United States, leading some
Americans to buy their pharmaceuticals by mail order or else join
bus trips across the border to fill their prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Prilosec, a popular ulcer medication, cost $400 for
100 capsules in New York but $184 in Canada and $107 in Mexico,
said Rep. Joseph Crowley, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ''Prescription drugs and medicines are not a luxury, they are a
necessity,'' added Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   High drug prices have emerged as a significant issue in this
year's political campaigns. Polling indicates the issue of
prescription drugs is a priority for Americans 65 and older, a
group that accounted for more than one-quarter of voters in the
1998 elections and is regarded as a key swing group in the fall
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans pushed a bill through the House last month that
would use private insurance and federal subsidies to cover some of
the cost of prescription drugs for senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has threatened to veto the legislation. He and
congressional Democrats are advocating a more encompassing but also
costlier alternative: a uniform, government-run prescription drug
benefit, offered to all 39 million elderly and disabled Medicare
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   FDA spokesman Lawrence Bachorik said the agency is concerned
that the House legislation could undermine its ''ability to protect
consumers and patients from substandard, poorly manufactured or
otherwise risky drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The FDA stands ready to work with Congress on these issues,''
he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-10-00 2045 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000710.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Green Bay, Packers Reach Name Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- In three years, naming rights to Lambeau
Field could go on sale for more than $120 million with the Packers
and the city of Green Bay splitting the proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Paul Jadin announced the deal Monday that would allow the
naming rights -- which are sold to a company for the right to put
its name on a property -- to go on sale in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   That's the target date for completing a $295 million expansion
and renovation of the stadium that the Packers contend is critical
to keep the team financially competitive in the National Football
League.
</P>
<P>
   The plan must clear several hurdles first.
</P>
<P>
   The naming rights could only be sold after an advisory
referendum in Brown County asks voters if they backed the sale. The
former City Stadium, built in 1957, was renamed in honor of the
team's founder and first coach, E.L. ''Curly'' Lambeau, after his
death in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   Jadin said he hoped any corporation that bought naming rights
would keep Lambeau in the name, ''like XYZ Co. at Lambeau Field.''
</P>
<P>
   Packers president Bob Harlan said the Packers initially wanted a
higher percentage of the naming-rights proceeds, but the team will
get all the revenue from other advertising, sponsorship and
promotional rights at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ''I kept hearing what the mayor and the city council said and
you don't get a negotiation finished until you keep working towards
the middle, and that's what we tried to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jadin said the Green Bay city council was expected to take up
the naming-rights deal Tuesday. If the council approves it, a new
stadium commission created under state law would be authorized to
vote to levy a half-percent sales tax in Brown County to help
finance the stadium improvements.
</P>
<P>
   First, voters would have to approve the sales tax in a
referendum tentatively planned for Sept. 12. The cornerstone of the
project is using the sales tax revenue to borrow $160 million for
the work.
</P>
<P>
   Brown County Executive Nancy Nusbaum said she was confident
voters would approve the sale, given the amount of money it could
raise as a way of reducing the taxpayers' share of the stadium
renovation.
</P>
<P>
   But Nusbaum doubted any corporation would agree to pay at least
$120 million for naming rights and keep Lambeau in the name.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is very much a business proposition,'' she said. ''There
is too great a risk that if Lambeau remains part of the name, it
gets too easy for the general public to ignore the corporate
name.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
