<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mudd Said Happy About Training Camp  </HEADLINE>
By HANK LOWENKRON
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Of all those headed with the Indianapolis
Colts to training camp on Thursday, offensive line coach Howard
Mudd might be the happiest.
</P>
<P>
   On April 27, the 58-year-old Mudd lost control of his motorcycle
and sustained multiple injuries. The injuries included a broken
shoulder, broken wrist, collapsed lung and a concussion when his
unhelmeted head struck the ground. His motorcycle and the car
involved in the collision that threw him in the air were both
demolished.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month after the accident, Mudd was back at work and
said Monday that his recovery makes the training camp in Terre
Haute, Ind., especially satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   ''When your life passes in front of you, literally, and I add up
what could have been, and what didn't happen, there's a very, very
large measure of gratitude for being alive. I've got some injuries,
but it's not like it could have been,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This will be Mudd's 27th consecutive NFL season as an offensive
line coach, and the three-time Pro Bowl starter as a member of the
San Francisco 49ers said the accident put football into a new
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ''In some respects it maybe helps me on a personal note, make me
realize that there are things more important,'' he said. ''Things
that I felt are less important, are maybe a little more important.
What does that mean? Maybe it is making sure some little detail is
not overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel differently coming into training camp this time.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows camp will be a little different because of some
lingering physical ailments from the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got some shoulder damage that I don't want to stick my hands
in somebody's chest to demonstrate, but that's about it. Before I
had some brain issues from banging my head,'' Mudd explained. ''But
other than that there are no limitations. I can run around and my
mouth still works and my voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Mudd will be working with an experienced line that helped
produce the biggest one-season turnaround in league history. The
Colts finished 13-3 last season after going 3-13 each of the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
   All five starters are back to open holes for running back
Edgerrin James, a Pro Bowl starter as a rookie last year, and
protect Pro Bowl quarterback Peyton Manning. That's a luxury the
Colts haven't had since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first year we were here as a team (1998), we had to learn
how to practice. We learned how to do that more than anything else,
what type of practice it takes to carry yourself through the game,
so that the game is less difficult,'' Mudd said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe very strongly that you play like you practice. The
players that we've got here now, they know how to practice, what
the standard of performance is and they like to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The starting unit has Adam Meadows and Tarik Glenn at tackle,
Larry Moore at center, with Steve McKinney and Waverly Jackson as
guards.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm blessed to have a core of players that know what we
want,'' Mudd said. ''An offensive line has to develop trust in each
other. When you're able to hold on to it from one year to the next,
there's certain levels that we expect. Now we've got a high water
mark to measure ourselves against. It's been decent. We've got to
do at least that well, and with the group we have I don't have as
much to do because there aren't as many that have to learn the
basics.''
</P>
<P>
   Mudd heads into camp looking at Jeff Saturday, who played some
as a rookie last season, for depth. Others he hopes may provide
depth include Tim Ridder, a 6-foot-7, 301-pounder from Notre Dame,
and Paul Snellings. Both Ridder and Snellings were with the team
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ''They know what we want, and it will be interesting to see how
they come along,'' Mudd said. ''We certainly need to find some
people, because we can't go with just six guys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
