<HEADLINE> Campaign To Support Family Planning  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- One of America's richest foundations launched a
multimillion-dollar education campaign Monday aimed at getting the
American public and the U.S. Congress to support family planning
programs around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year campaign, funded by The David and Lucile Packard
Foundation, is backed by leading women's, children's and
environmental groups who say family planning is the key to saving
the lives of mothers, children and planet Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ''For so many years the adversaries of family planning have been
very loud and very vocal,'' said Gloria Feldt, president of Planned
Parenthood Federation of America, Inc., one of the partners in the
campaign. ''I think it is high time for the message of the
importance of being able to plan and space your family to be out
there just as strongly as the adversaries are delivering their
message.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which is receiving about $13 million from the
Packard foundation for the first year, plans to deliver several
messages in television, newspaper and magazine advertisements as
well as at meetings with lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ''International family planning can reduce population pressures
on our planet,'' said John Flicker, president of the National
Audubon Society, another campaign partner. ''It is our best
opportunity to address the single most important root cause of
environmental degradation.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is also stressing that family planning could save
about 3 million children's lives a year by helping women to space
births at least two years apart, and it could save the lives of
some of the 600,000 women who die every year from complications of
pregnancy and childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   ''The simple truth is that a lot of couples don't plan their
families because they can't,'' said Amy Coen, president of
Population Action International. ''One hundred fifty million
married women in the developing world would use family planning
services if they were available. They are not.''
</P>
<P>
   Participants said the campaign would serve to remind the
American public that the United States is no longer playing a
leadership role in international family planning, primarily because
anti-abortion forces in Congress have cut funding for overseas
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign partners also include CARE and Save the Children.
</P>
<P>
   In a message for World Population Day on Tuesday,
Secretary-General Kofi Annan stressed the need to stabilize world
population and ensure that women can make key decisions about their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ''Too many girls do not have the same chance of education as
boys. Too many women still cannot choose when or whether to become
pregnant. Too many women resort to abortions that are not safe,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: PLANet public awareness campaign
</P>
<P>
   http://www.familyplanet.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
