<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 49ers Safety McDonald Retires  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- Safety Tim McDonald, released five
months ago by the San Francisco 49ers, retired Monday after 13 NFL
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald, who played in the Pro Bowl six times, was released by
the 49ers in February as the team struggled to get under the salary
cap.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald, 35, was one of several veterans asked to renegotiate
his contract and reduce his salary, and he was cut when a deal
could not be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald spent the first six years of his pro career with the
Arizona Cardinals before joining the 49ers in 1993 as a free agent.
He started 111 out of 112 possible games for San Francisco, and
earned a Super Bowl ring in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   He said Monday he had considered playing for only one other
team, the Carolina Panthers, who are coached by former 49ers coach
George Seifert.
</P>
<P>
   ''I finally realized that there was just no way I could have
given the type of energy and commitment that it takes. I realize
that it is time to say 'No' to the abuse to my body and time to say
'Yes' to my family and other interests,'' he said. ''I gave so much
of my heart and desire to the 49ers.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco general manager Bill Walsh said McDonald was a
great athlete and a team leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tim was one of the greatest performers in contemporary
football and there are those who would state flatly that he was the
best strong safety to ever play the game,'' Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald, who said he will focus on running his World Sports
Cafe in Fresno, said it was time to move on after 10 operations and
several concussions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
