<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wis. Travel Firm Settles Complaint  </HEADLINE>
By D. IAN HOPPER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As part of a federal crackdown on travel
fraud, a Wisconsin company and its managers have settled charges
that they lured customers with ''free'' trips only to make them pay
hundreds of dollars each.
</P>
<P>
   Defendants James Burns and John Bundy will be permanently banned
from travel-related telemarketing for misrepresenting the value of
the trips or telling consumers that they had won free vacations,
according to the Federal Trade Commission complaint. Both men were
senior officers at First Impressions, which also operated under the
name ''Air-Land-Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Consumers should never have to pay phantom charges to collect
a so-called free vacation,'' said Jodie Bernstein, head of the
FTC's consumer protection bureau. ''When you hear the words,
'you've won a free vacation,' ask about the fees. A healthy dose of
skepticism may save you a suitcase full of money.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is the latest in the FTC's ''Operation Trip
Trap,'' a series of complaints against 25 travel companies
presented last August. The FTC filed suit against five companies --
three are now settled, including the one announced Monday --
accusing them of deceptive practices. An additional 20 companies
faced charges by state regulators.
</P>
<P>
   According to the FTC complaint, consumers filled out postcards
at restaurants, fairs and other events, believing they were
entering a drawing for free vacations. Air-Land-Sea representatives
called the consumers telling them that they had won an
all-inclusive vacation package at popular locations such as
Orlando, Fla., or Cancun, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Then the representatives told consumers that ''incidental''
charges ranging up to $299 per person had to be paid separately, as
well as port fees. Additional travelers had to pay extra, and once
on the trip, consumers found they had to pay ''upgrade'' fees at
the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the consumers sometimes found their cruise or hotel
wasn't paid for, and many were pressured into attending day-long
timeshare presentations.
</P>
<P>
   The company's consumers have already recieved more than $600,000
in reimbursements since the case was filed, according to the FTC.
</P>
<P>
   Between July of 1998 and 1999, the FTC received nearly 2,500
travel-related complaints worth more than $610,000 in alleged
consumer losses. Of those complaints, nearly a third were against
companies based in Florida.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-10-00 2134 </TRAILER>
