<TEXT>
<P>
 Mon, July 10, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House OK's Easing Drug Import Rules
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amid growing public resentment of high prescription drug
prices, the House voted overwhelmingly today to prevent the government from
discouraging the purchase of drugs in Canada or other countries. An increasing
number of Americans have been going to Canada, Mexico and other countries to
purchase prescription drugs cheaper than what they cost in the United States.
Technically, it's illegal to import prescription drugs that were originally made
in the United States, and the Food and Drug Administration sometimes sends
warning letters to people caught doing it.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Barak Heads to U.S. Summit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- After narrowly surviving a no-confidence vote, Prime
Minister Ehud Barak on Monday headed to the U.S. summit meeting on the Middle
East. ''The government did not fall and I am continuing onward to Camp David,''
a grim Barak said, minutes after the opposition Likud party failed to muster the
necessary 61 votes in parliament to topple his government. The no-confidence
motion gathered 54 votes to 52 for Barak.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ex-Starr Aide Responds on Leak
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Accused of misleading a judge about a news leak in the
Monica Lewinsky case, a former Kenneth Starr aide suggested today that
independent counsel lawyers were to blame. In a pretrial brief, Charles Bakaly
alleged that he detailed his role in a disputed January 1999 story to lawyers
for Starr's office, but they narrowed his account before filing a legal
statement on his behalf.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
$196B Sought From Big Tobacco
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Smokers in a Florida class-action trial asked a jury today for
a record $196 billion to punish the tobacco industry. ''Never have so few caused
so much harm to so many for so long, and the day of reckoning has arrived,''
said attorney Stanley Rosenblatt as closing arguments began in the two-year case
involving up to 700,000 sick Florida smokers. It could be the gravest legal
threat ever to the five biggest U.S. cigarette makers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. To Stockpile Heating Oil
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton decided today to stockpile 2 million
barrels of heating oil in the Northeast as refineries concentrate on pumping out
as much gasoline as possible. He directed Energy Secretary Bill Richardson to
trade oil from the government's Strategic Petroleum Reserve for refined heating
oil that will be put into Northeast storage tanks. The goal is to have the fuel
in place within 90 days.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Urges Honest Politics
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- In a valedictory address to the National
Governors' Association, President Clinton today appealed for civility amid
election-year politics and took broad credit for the nation's economic success.
''I ask you to help ensure an election season that is positive, open and
vigorous about the real and honest differences, but devoid of the poison that
has too often clouded the judgment of everybody involved in the public
process,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Opposes Bush on Missiles
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore said today the failure of a
test for a national missile defense system does not mean the idea is doomed, and
he criticized the version supported by GOP presidential foe George W. Bush as
''more expensive and less likely to work.'' The Democratic presidential
contender, answering online questions -- using The Washington Post's Web site,
said Bush's proposal is ''calculated to destroy arms control agreements with
Russia.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Consumer Borrowing Rises
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans borrowed money freely in May, ringing up the
biggest rise in consumer credit since the beginning of the year, the Federal
Reserve said today. Total consumer credit rose a seasonally adjusted $11.8
billion in May for an annual growth rate of 9.8 percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 11; Nasdaq Loses 43
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in a quiet session today as investors
traded cautiously ahead of this week's corporate earnings reports. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 10.60 to 10,646.58. On the NYSE, gainers led losers by
5-to-3. The Nasdaq fell 42.91 to 3,980.29.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Horror Spoof Takes Box Office
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The horror film parody ''Scary Movie,'' a gross-out
comedy, took in $42.3 million in its opening weekend, the best debut ever for an
R-rated movie and the second-highest premiere this year, after ''Mission:
Impossible 2.'' It beat the recent openings of ''The Perfect Storm'' at $41.3
million and ''The Patriot'' at $22.4 million.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Coach Brown To Stay With Sixers
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Larry Brown, who once dreamed of coaching at North
Carolina, is staying with the Philadelphia 76ers. Brown announced his decision
today after meeting with North Carolina officials over the weekend to discuss
the vacancy at his alma mater. Coach George Karl of the Milwaukee Bucks also
declined to pursue the Tar Heels post.
</P>
