<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wyoming Wildfire Contained  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCK SPRINGS, Wyo. (AP) -- Firefighters contained a wildfire
Monday that burned 36,700 acres of juniper and sagebrush just north
of the Utah border.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is contained, but control is still going to be awhile,''
Bureau of Land Management spokesman Mike Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire, between Flaming Gorge Reservoir and U.S. 191 south of
Rock Springs, was declared contained at 6 p.m. No injuries were
reported nor structures lost since the fire was sparked by
lightning July 2.
</P>
<P>
   Lower temperatures, higher humidity and spotty showers helped
firefighters bring the fire under control over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the fire burned dense stands of juniper. Wind-whipped
flames that reached 20 to 70 feet forced the closure of several
Sweetwater County roads and threatened a power line.
</P>
<P>
   The fire also caused a spectacular smoke plume visible from Rock
Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, the fire weakened, becoming a smoldering
ground fire with some isolated torching of juniper stands.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, fire officials began pulling firefighters away from
an 11,033-acre fire, hoping to keep them rested in case more large
fires break out.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the National Interagency Fire Center said the
lightning-sparked blaze, which has burned land in and around the
Dinosaur National Monument in extreme northwestern Colorado, should
be fully contained Tuesday or Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Fire information officer Dennis Saville said the fire was 95
percent contained Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend two other major wildfires in western Colorado
were brought under control. The Cone Mountain fire near Gateway
burned 4,580 acres and the blaze near Rangely burned 1,700 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, firefighters were working to extinguish two
lightning-caused fires in Wyoming's Grand Teton National Park. Both
fires, which started Sunday, were less than an acre.
</P>
<P>
   Other smaller fires were contained over the weekend east of Rock
Springs, near Medicine Bow National Forest, west of Cheyenne and in
the Big Horn Mountains in north-central Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Interagency Coordination Center:
http://www.nifc.gov/news/nicc.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
