<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White Supremacist's Trial Underway  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA DEUTSCH
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Lawyers for white supremacist Buford O.
Furrow moved Monday to dismiss numerous charges against him,
claiming legal flaws in his indictment on hate-crime allegations in
a shooting at a Jewish community center.
</P>
<P>
   Among the claims in six separate defense motions is an argument
that the North Valley Jewish Community Center does not fall within
legal definitions of places covered by civil rights hate crime
statutes.
</P>
<P>
   Five counts of the indictment contend that on Aug. 10 Furrow
shot and wounded three boys, a teen-age girl and a receptionist at
the center while they were ''enjoying the goods, services,
facilities, privileges and advantages of the North Valley Jewish
Community Center, a place of exhibition and entertainment which
serves the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers said that in fact the center exists to serve the Jewish
community, not the public at large.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said that while the center may open some of its
programs to nonmembers ''it serves not the public, but the Jewish
community, Jewish heritage and Jewish way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The original indictment in the case did not address the Jewish
Community Center shootings, but it was later superseded to include
those charges. The defense asked that they be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Central to the indictment is a murder charge accusing Furrow,
37, of fatally shooting Filipino-American letter carrier Joseph
Ileto on the same day as the community center attack. The
government seeks the death penalty on that charge.
</P>
<P>
   The defense motions indicated there will probably be a mental
illness defense for Furrow, either in the guilt phase or penalty
phase of his trial, but the lawyers have not given official notice
of their intent.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Attorney's spokeswoman said prosecutors had not studied
the motions yet and would have no comment. They have until August
to file responses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
