<HEADLINE> Deaths in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressHenri Gault:
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Henri Gault, a food critic and co-founder of the
GaultMillau food guide that helped launch nouvelle cuisine around
the world, died Monday of a heart attack. He was 70.
</P>
<P>
   Gault and Christian Millau founded the annual GaultMillau
restaurant guide in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   With its colorful comments on food, atmosphere and decor that
blended feisty criticism with warm praise, the guide quickly caught
on among the French. It went on to become a serious rival to the
more established Michelin guide.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants in the GaultMillau guide are rated on a score of
1-20, and chefs awarded a maximum of four ''toques,'' or chefs'
hats. The Michelin guide awards a maximum of three ''macaroons,''
or stars, for restaurants rated ''worth the journey.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Gault's best-known works are ''Gault and Millau Eat
Dinner,'' ''My 50 Best Restaurants in France,'' ''Europe's Top 300
Restaurants'' and ''The Guide to Foreign Restaurants in Paris.''
Robert Hutchinson:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Robert Hutchinson, a horse racing aficionado who
ran an advertising agency and published trucking magazines, died
July 3 of complications from a fall. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson worked at the Western (Advertising) Agency, founded
by his father, Brubaker Hutchinson, an early partner in Longacres
Race Course. Western, based in Seattle, became Newport Publication
Group, which published several trucking-industry periodicals.
</P>
<P>
   After his father died in 1962, Hutchinson became a partner in
the track and served as secretary-treasurer of the Washington
Jockey Club until Longacres closed on Sept. 21,1992, after a
59-year run.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his second wife, four sons, two daughters, and
six grandchildren.
Vahe Oshagan:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Vahe Oshagan, critically acclaimed
Armenian-language poet, died June 30 of complications from heart
surgery. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   He was famed in Armenian intellectual circles for his eight
volumes of poetry, six volumes of fiction, and many short stories,
plays and commentaries. Most of his works were written in Armenian
but some have been translated into English.
</P>
<P>
   Oshagan is credited with having revolutionized Armenian poetry
by rejecting its imposed formality, often writing in colloquial
language. He was also hailed for giving a voice to the Armenian
diaspora.
Warren Reynolds:
</P>
<P>
   GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) -- Warren Reynolds, a broadcaster who
spent 36 years at television station WOOD, including 31 years as
sports director, died Sunday of prostate cancer. He was 63.
</P>
<P>
   Reynold's father, legendary sports announcer Bob Reynolds, was
sports director of Detroit radio station WJR for 25 years and
announced Detroit Lions and Michigan State University football
games.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Reynolds announced Spartans games with his father.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Reynolds arrived at WOOD as sports director in 1964
and held the post until 1995. He remained an air personality at the
station with his ''Community Network 8'' and ''Positively
Michigan'' broadcast segments.
</P>
<P>
   He recently became the first recipient of the Grand Rapids
Sports Hall of Fame's lifetime achievement award.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, four children and eight
grandchildren.
Harold Sack:
</P>
<P>
   OCEANSIDE, N.Y. (AP) -- Harold Sack, America's foremost period
furniture dealer who paid $12.1 million for an 18th century Newport
desk-bookcase in 1989, died Saturday. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   Sack bought the mahogany secretary at Christie's for what was
then the highest auction price ever for an item other than a
painting.
</P>
<P>
   The desk, which he bought for a Texas financier, originally was
owned by Nicholas Brown, of Providence, R.I., and his family, for
whom Brown University is named.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1960s to the 1990s, Sack shattered auction price
records for American furniture. In 1977, he set the record of
$135,000 when he bought a Boston bombe chest. Three years later, he
pushed the record to $396,000, for a block-front Newport chest.
</P>
<P>
   He set the record again in 1983, paying $687,500 for a Newport
kneehole desk at Sotheby's.
Parke Thompson:
</P>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio (AP) -- Parke Thompson, who was described in The
Guinness Book of Records as being one of the world's most-traveled
people, died Sunday from a heart aneurysm. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson once said that receiving the 1989 Guinness edition,
which included a photo of him at the South Pole as the
most-traveled man, was the realization of a dream. He got the honor
by visiting 309 countries, territories and island groups in the
world, as defined by Guinness. He was listed in the book from 1984
to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Travel had been a passion since Thompson's grandparents took him
to England and Germany when he was 7. He spent more than 31 years
seeing the world through the viewfinder of his camera.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who also had a 55-year law practice, shot more than
70,000 photos on the 37 trips it took to achieve the record. His
journeys provided the basis of ''Around the World in 60 Minutes,''
a slide show he presented for community and private groups, and
helped illustrate a Life magazine profile on him in May 1987.
Laurel Vlock:
</P>
<P>
   WOODBRIDGE, Conn. (AP) -- Laurel Vlock, a producer and director
whose films about Holocaust survivors served as models for Steven
Spielberg's Shoah Foundation, died Saturday from injuries sustained
in a car accident. She was 74.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979 she founded the Holocaust Survivors Film Project Inc.,
which videotaped testimony from Holocaust survivors. The films are
deposited at the Fortunoff Video Archive for Holocaust Testimonies
at Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   Vlock won an Emmy Award in 1981 for ''Forever Yesterday,'' a
documentary about Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Vlock had hosted the television program ''Dialogue with Laurel
Vlock'' since 1966. Her other television credits include ''Meet the
President'' in 1978.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
