<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan: Serb Massacre To Haunt UN  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- On the fifth anniversary of the worst
massacre in Europe since World War II, Secretary-General Kofi Annan
said the United Nations' failure to help save thousands of Bosnian
Muslims from a Serb mass murder will forever haunt the world body.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of disarmed and defenseless men and boys who had been
led to believe that the United Nations would ensure their safety
were killed in the forests around Srebrenica, Annan said in a
statement to mark Tuesday's anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Starting July 11, 1995, just a few months before the end of the
3&AMP;frac12;-year war, Bosnian Serb forces overran the eastern town, which
was designated a U.N.-protected zone. When the slaughter was
finished, as many as 8,000 men and boys older than 14 were missing.
The remains of some 2,500 have been exhumed.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing his ''deepest regret and remorse'' to the families of
the victims, the secretary-general said ''we cannot undo this
tragedy, but it is vitally important that the right lessons be
learned and applied in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The tragedy of Srebrenica will forever haunt the history of
the United Nations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said it was important not to be forget that the architects
of the Srebrenica massacre have been indicted by the U.N. war
crimes tribunal but remain at large.
</P>
<P>
   ''This fact alone suggests that the most important lesson of
Srebrenica -- that we must recognize evil for what it is, and
confront it not with expediency and compromise but with implacable
resistance -- has yet to be fully learned and applied,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a report in December on the 1995 massacres, Annan said the
United Nations failed to help save the Bosnian Muslims because of
errors, misjudgment and ''an inability to recognize the scope of
the evil confronting us.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan, who headed U.N. peacekeeping operations during the war in
Bosnia, said the United Nations treated Serbs and Muslims equally
when they should have made a ''moral judgment'' that the Serbs'
campaign of ethnic cleansing was evil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
