<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Mon, July 10, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S. Korea Bank Workers Strike
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Tens of thousands of bank workers went on strike
Tuesday after failing to obtain government guarantees for their job security.
The union is concerned the government's plans to restructure the industry would
spur bank mergers and lead to layoffs. The initial impact appeared limited, as
banks opened using non-union employees or union members who opposed the walkout.
Last-minute efforts to prevent the strike ended after bank union leaders walked
out of talks with government officials which lasted 6&AMP;frac12; hours.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nation Faces Blood Shortage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- An ever-increasing demand for blood combined with summer's
customary donor drop-off have created a critical nationwide shortage, blood bank
officials said today. The American Red Cross said there is a need for all blood
types. The shortage has reached crisis proportions in the New York metropolitan
region, said Dr. Robert Jones, president and CEO of the New York Blood Center.
He said the shortage has forced the center to reduce blood shipments to New York
and New Jersey hospitals by as much as 75 percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House OK's Easing Drug Import Rules
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amid growing public resentment of high prescription drug
prices, the House voted overwhelmingly today to prevent the government from
discouraging the purchase of drugs in Canada or other countries. An increasing
number of Americans have been going to Canada, Mexico and other countries to
purchase prescription drugs cheaper than what they cost in the United States.
Technically, it's illegal to import prescription drugs that were originally made
in the United States, and the Food and Drug Administration sometimes sends
warning letters to people caught doing it.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Barak Leaves for Camp David Summit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister Ehud Barak on Monday headed to the U.S.
summit meeting on the Middle East, after narrowly surviving a no-confidence
vote. ''The government did not fall and I am continuing onward to Camp David,''
a grim Barak said, minutes after the opposition Likud party failed to muster the
necessary 61 votes in parliament to topple his government. The no-confidence
motion gathered 54 votes to 52 for Barak.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Smokers Seek Up to $196 Billion
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Smokers in a Florida class-action trial asked a jury today for
a record $196 billion to punish the tobacco industry. ''Never have so few caused
so much harm to so many for so long, and the day of reckoning has arrived,''
said attorney Stanley Rosenblatt as closing arguments began in the two-year case
involving up to 700,000 sick Florida smokers. It could be the gravest legal
threat ever to the five biggest U.S. cigarette makers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Wants Heating Oil Reserve
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton decided today to stockpile 2 million
barrels of heating oil in the Northeast as refineries concentrate on pumping out
as much gasoline as possible. He directed Energy Secretary Bill Richardson to
trade oil from the government's Strategic Petroleum Reserve for refined heating
oil that will be put into Northeast storage tanks. The goal is to have the fuel
in place within 90 days.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Opposes Bush on Missiles
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore said today the failure of a
test for a national missile defense system does not mean the idea is doomed, and
he criticized the version supported by GOP presidential foe George W. Bush as
''more expensive and less likely to work.'' The Democratic presidential
contender, answering online questions -- using The Washington Post's Web site,
said Bush's proposal is ''calculated to destroy arms control agreements with
Russia.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Slip in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell moderately early Tuesday on selling of
technology issues, while the dollar was higher against the yen. The benchmark
225-issue Nikkei shed 70.19 points, or 0.40 percent, to 17,502.49 in the first
30 minutes of trading. On Monday, the average closed up 174.44 points, or 1.00
percent. On the stock market, the Nikkei index started lower after the
technology-heavy Nasdaq fell 42.91 points to 3,980.29 at Monday's close on Wall
Street. The Dow Jones average rose 10.60 points to end at 10,646.58.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Green Bay, Packers Reach Name Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- In three years, naming rights to Lambeau Field could
go on sale for more than $120 million with the Packers and the city of Green Bay
splitting the proceeds. Mayor Paul Jadin announced the deal Monday that would
allow the naming rights -- which are sold to a company for the right to put its
name on a property -- to go on sale in 2003. That's the target date for
completing a $295 million expansion and renovation of the stadium that the
Packers contend is critical to keep the team financially competitive in the
National Football League.
The plan must clear several hurdles first. 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER
</SUBHEAD>
