<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haas ties for Lead at Public Links  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Defending champion Hunter Haas shot a
1-under par 71 Monday to finish in a five-way tie for the lead
after the first round of the U.S. Amateur Public Links
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Haas, 23, from Norman, Okla., was tied with Mark Farrell, Andy
Roberts, Brad Nurski and Jimmy Walker. They were the only golfers
to shoot under par on the 6,869-yard, par-72 Great Blue Course at
Heron Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Links Championship, in its 75th year, is limited to
players who do not belong to private clubs. The ''blue collar
championship'' is sponsored by the United States Golf Association.
</P>
<P>
   The field of 156 will continue stroke play on Tuesday. The low
64 golfers will begin match play on Wednesday, and the championship
will be held Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Haas, who won last year at Alton, Ill., is trying to become the
first repeat winner since Billy Tuten won in 1982 and 1983. Only
three others have done it.
</P>
<P>
   ''The course played a little more difficult than it would look
like it was set up to play,'' Haas said. ''I'm surprised because I
thought there would be a lot more birdies out there. I could have
had a few more birdies, but putts didn't go in.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, 20, who plays at Brescia University in Owensboro, Ky.,
had two double-bogeys but also had seven birdies, tops in the
round.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was one of the best putting days I've ever had,'' the
5-foot-7, 120-pound Roberts said. ''I made four putts longer than
30 feet for birdie. I was up and down all day. I wanted to create
room the first day so that I could be comfortable making match
play, which is my goal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
