<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000710.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-10 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Says It's Being Cheated  </HEADLINE>
By D. IAN HOPPER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- AT&AMP;T accused Verizon Communications Monday of
illegally steering New York customers who call for local phone
service to its own long distance service.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T said Verizon, formerly Bell Atlantic, has violated
regulations by failing to have ''marketing neutrality'' in selling
long distance service to its customers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bell Atlantic is doing exactly the opposite of what the
Telecommunications Act of 1996 intended. Instead of vigorous
competition on a level playing field, Bell Atlantic's marketing
strategy is to leverage its dominance of the local phone market to
stifle long distance competition,'' said Robert M. Aquilina, senior
vice president of AT&AMP;T's consumer services unit. ''New Yorkers who
call Bell Atlantic for local phone service are not being properly
informed of their long distance choices.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has asked the Federal Communications Commission to force
Verizon to pay damages, and stop Verizon from providing long
distance service in New York.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T said it used an outside marketing firm to conduct a survey
earlier this year, finding that in nearly half of test calls, Bell
Atlantic representatives mentioned only Bell Atlantic long distance
service. In two thirds of test cases, AT&AMP;T said, callers weren't
told they had a choice of long distance carriers.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T also alleged that in 5 percent of calls, Bell Atlantic
illegally used information about a customer's existing long
distance service in order to market Bell Atlantic's service.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon spokesman Eric Rabe said that the test calls were made
by customers looking to add a second phone line. In that situation,
Rabe said, the representative is not required to read the list of
long distance options.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think AT&AMP;T is misinterpreting what the rules are,'' Rabe
said. ''And the FCC sees it how we see it.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T confirmed that the marketing firm called about second
lines, but that it doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''The law applies whether it's first or second lines,'' AT&AMP;T
spokesman Jim McGann said. ''They're required to be a neutral party
regardless.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Verizon official said that this is another case of AT&AMP;T
blaming other companies for its own problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''In this case, the problem is that hundreds of thousands of
customers are happily deserting AT&AMP;T for Verizon long distance
service in New York,'' said Edward D. Young III, Verizon's senior
vice president for federal government relations.
</P>
<P>
   Rabe said Verizon does comply with non-discrimination rules for
first-time customers.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first battle the two companies have fought in New
York. In March, AT&AMP;T asked the FCC to suspend Bell Atlantic's
authority to provide long distance there because of broken systems
that serve competitors. AT&AMP;T said that customers choosing their
service had their orders ''lost or mishandled'' by Bell Atlantic,
and it took customers several months to change their service
provider.
</P>
<P>
   A comment by Rabe shows the hostility between the
telecommunications behemoths.
</P>
<P>
   ''Instead of saying they've got confusing plans that are too
expensive, they're saying Bell Atlantic is doing something
underhanded,'' Rabe said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
